Fascinating! The bernal afternoon selas phenomenon continues to produce! First got on an adult male in the south side PoMs with a gray-headed OCWA. Next two males were seen in the Crappy Eucs guarding their own PoMs respectively. A third adult male was seen simultaneously looking on in envy from high in the eucs. A female came in with a male and female ANHU and flashed her insanely broad outer tails in front of me. Then she flew away to chase an im male RUHU which I manage to nab a tail spread of. This is my most conservative count, realistically there were probably between 6-10 RUHU present, but anyone who has tried counting hummingbirds 1x1 can empathize with knowing how difficult they are to count; so I am leaving this total at the most conservative possible.

Observation Details: ***Very rare--continuing bird apparently present since the 17th or 18th, but first reported last night by Derek Lovitch. Found by homeowners. Imm. male Selasphorus hummer with a fair amount of orange on the flanks, rump, tail, and nape, and most remaining green around the back, crown, and shoulders. Showed clean white bib, white throat speckled with rows of dark feathers. Made three stops at the feeder, and visited the flower baskets along the top floor windows along the front of the house, working right to left, and perched several times in a larger apple-ish looking tree with small red fruits. Also perched in a small bare shrub by the white picket fence gate, and twice disappeared into a hemlock in the side yard. Also visited low flowers in front foundation garden. I did not obtain any photos of the spread tail, but Louis Bevier did and confirmed this as a Rufous (as opposed to Allen's) Louis's notes here *Called several times while hovering around a perch, a sharp chip reminding me very much of a DEJU. Also acted aggressively towards PISIs, sometimes chasing them away from the feeders. ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Derek's notes on viewing the bird: "The bird is at 97 Ledgewood Drive in Yarmouth. Ledgewood is a lightly traveled neighborhood road, but it is rather narrow. Please park along one side of the road only (the homeowner’s side/odd numbers) so as not to block traffic. Please be sure not to block any driveways, and avoid turning around in driveways whenever possible. We saw numerous young children out on bikes despite the weather, so please drive very slowly and carefully. Once at the house, walk to the white picket fence on the RIGHT side of the house. The small hummingbird feeder is on the backside of the bay window. The best line for observations and photographs is several feet to the right of the gate. Under no circumstances should anyone enter the yard, neighboring yard, or walk in, through, or on any garden beds. Please include the above instructions in EVERY eBird or any other post...We cannot let people show up with only a GPS location or address and assume they’ll figure out where to see the feeder or where not to be a bother."
Photos:

Continuing beauty. Second time Ive had the pleasure to see one of these cuties..I hope she survives. She came to the feeder drinking long pulls several times then off to tree tops in between. She looks healthy and content.

Presumed immature rufous hummingbird first reported yesterday at a private residence. Behaviorally this hummingbird would perch at a prominent location just outside the feeding area and watch for "intruding" hummingbirds - swiftly chasing any away. At regular intervals it would hover over the feeding area looking down and around, moving from viewing spot to viewing spot then after a short while return to its watch perch. It did this over and over and over again, viewing from the same points in the air, and then every few rounds work in some feeding time, too. Interesting behavior, I have not seen any ruby-throats patrol like that. As for physical ID, I am not familiar with either rufous or Allen's hummingbirds. I've included 2 shots where the tail feathers are in a partial spread. I see in Sibley's the two outer tail feathers of an Allen's are narrower than the others; here the two outer feathers look proportionately the same width as the third feather in both shots. Please note, the homeowner wishes to remain private and the checklist pin is just a generic location.

Continuing for several days. Seen about three times between about 8:45 and 9:00 AM, the  first two times mostly the underside of the tail and vent area, as the bird was perched on the opposite side of a feeder. Also seen by the homeowner during the first few minutes perched in its favorite tree, but I could not see it there. Possibly shot by again at about 9:30.  Not banded by Bruce Peterjohn, but from his review of the photos, he thought this was a Rufous Hummingbird, based on the relatively broad outer tail feathers, and because "the second rectrix (R2) appears to have a slight but noticeable emargination that would indicate it is a Rufous Hummingbird." He also stated that "The bird is clearly a female based on the green central rectrices, but I would not want to speculate on its age based on the tail pattern. Young females tend to have slightly broader outer rectrices than adults, but there is considerable overlap and any differences are measured in tenths of millimeters that would be difficult to judge based solely on photos." See spread tail photo by Max Wilson at (https://macaulaylibrary.org/asset/392350141).  See photos. Many thanks to the homeowners for allowing visits.

*Rare. Homeowner reports the bird has been present for roughly 2 weeks. An immature male/adult female Selasphorus hummingbird, with rufous flanks, a green back, and a patch of red gorget feathers. At the time of observation, we were unable to obtain spread tail photos, but many photos were taken of the bird.  Upon review of photos taken this morning by Matt Misewicz, the spread tail seems to show wide outer retrices suggesting this bird is a Rufous, rather than an Allen's Hummingbird. I feel comfortable counting it as such - unless the bird ends up getting banded and new information regarding it's ID arises.  Homeowners are alright with people viewing the hummingbird, please park on the street and view from the sidewalk unless invited up. The feeder is in their front yard, on the right side of the house on their porch.

Summary: Continuing. Goal was to trap/band/measure fifth rectrix tail feather and rule out Allen's Hummingbird. The hummingbird was not successfully trapped, despite "herculean" efforts by Bob Yunick (bander), "Dillon" (assistant bander from Albany Pine Bush preserve), and the homeowner. Bob was able to view the hummingbird for approximately five hours, and was able to view my documentary photos of the fan/spread tail feathers, and gorget photos. Based on five hours of viewing/ seeing behavior/ and looking at my photos, Bob Yunick believes this hummingbird to be a hatch year female Rufous Hummingbird. Bob was able to view my tail fan/ spread photos and the fifth rectrix tail feather does not seem to have the narrow fifth rectrix. The shape of tail feathers did not indicate Allen's. There were no identifiable characteristics to indicate Allen's. Bob used Peterson's Hummingbird Guide of North America by Sheri L. Williamson and compared the plates to my 8/9/22 photos (see my ebird report-same date to see some of the same photos I showed Bob). The photos did not match perfectly to any of the plates, although it more aligned with Rufous Hummingbird. Although Bob could not view hummingbird in hand (to see two line striation in bill indicating juvenile), his views and hummingbird's behavior indicated likely juvenile. Re: "herculean" efforts to trap hummingbird: Homeowner doesn't have a hummingbird feeder, thus the hummingbird has been feeding on flowers. Bob's trapping system is a hummingbird feeder in a net surround. The net is lifted half way up the feeder, and has a long attached line to where Bob is seated. In cases where a hummingbird is familiar to a feeder, once hummingbird enters the net surround and starts to feed, Bob would be able to release line and net would drop before hummingbird could escape net surround. This hummingbird was not familiar with the feeder and took many steps to feed anywhere and everywhere except the feeder. *For five hours!*.  Bob, his assistant , the homeowner and I came up with many revised steps. The hummingbird feeder was decorated with the hummingbird's favorite flowers, the inside of the net surround contained its favorite flowers.  A large/ heavy planter with its favorite flowers was moved underneath the net surround. The hummingbird fed on all the flowers except the ones near the feeder. The hummingbird started to feed near the planted flowers, and the homeowner covered the favored planted flowers with bed sheets. The hummingbird would feed on the flowers below the sheet, and tried to fly up under the sheet. Then, the hummingbird fed elsewhere in the garden, and the assistant and I sat at the two other planted areas that the hummingbird started feeding, in hopes that seeing us so close to the other planted areas may thwart the hummingbird and send it back to the feeder area. That helped somewhat, but the hummingbird only came close to going inside the net area once (in five hours), but hummingbird was hesitant and hovering closer to the net.  It would have escaped when Bob let net down, and then the hummingbird would be frightened and not return.  The bander left, and then the Ruby-throated Hummingbird landed on a branch in a nearby tree. The Rufous Hummingbird flew in and perched four inches away from the Ruby-throated(!) (that had been dive bombing it). This is not territorial adult behavior. New goal: homeowner is going to set up hummingbird feeder in yard, hoping that this hummingbird will observe local Ruby-throated hummingbirds (there seems to be some territorial disputes between the Ruby-throated and Rufous) and get familiar with the feeder (over a period of days).  And then perhaps then try banding again.  That's *if* hummingbird stays around, and *if* after discussing with bander he feels there may be success in trapping, and he has availability.  This location is private and homeowner hasn't opened location to the birding public. I have included my long notation here, as I have had many messages asking me for this information. I did not take out my camera to use, until after the bander left.  He hasn't seen photos attached to today's report. Photos continue to show tail fan/spread, which also make Rufous Hummingbird seem more likely. Edit: I want to mention that the Ruby-throated Hummingbird was enticed by feeder set-up and was trapped and banded by Bob.

Media notes: At feeder. Manual, f/7.1, ISO 400, 1/125 sec
Observation Details: ***Very rare--continuing bird apparently present since the 17th or 18th, but first reported last night by Derek Lovitch. Found by homeowners. Imm. male Selasphorus hummer with a fair amount of orange on the flanks, rump, tail, and nape, and most remaining green around the back, crown, and shoulders. Showed clean white bib, white throat speckled with rows of dark feathers. Made three stops at the feeder, and visited the flower baskets along the top floor windows along the front of the house, working right to left, and perched several times in a larger apple-ish looking tree with small red fruits. Also perched in a small bare shrub by the white picket fence gate, and twice disappeared into a hemlock in the side yard. Also visited low flowers in front foundation garden. I did not obtain any photos of the spread tail, but Louis Bevier did and confirmed this as a Rufous (as opposed to Allen's) Louis's notes here *Called several times while hovering around a perch, a sharp chip reminding me very much of a DEJU. Also acted aggressively towards PISIs, sometimes chasing them away from the feeders. ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Derek's notes on viewing the bird: "The bird is at 97 Ledgewood Drive in Yarmouth. Ledgewood is a lightly traveled neighborhood road, but it is rather narrow. Please park along one side of the road only (the homeowner’s side/odd numbers) so as not to block traffic. Please be sure not to block any driveways, and avoid turning around in driveways whenever possible. We saw numerous young children out on bikes despite the weather, so please drive very slowly and carefully. Once at the house, walk to the white picket fence on the RIGHT side of the house. The small hummingbird feeder is on the backside of the bay window. The best line for observations and photographs is several feet to the right of the gate. Under no circumstances should anyone enter the yard, neighboring yard, or walk in, through, or on any garden beds. Please include the above instructions in EVERY eBird or any other post...We cannot let people show up with only a GPS location or address and assume they’ll figure out where to see the feeder or where not to be a bother."

Fascinating! The bernal afternoon selas phenomenon continues to produce! First got on an adult male in the south side PoMs with a gray-headed OCWA. Next two males were seen in the Crappy Eucs guarding their own PoMs respectively. A third adult male was seen simultaneously looking on in envy from high in the eucs. A female came in with a male and female ANHU and flashed her insanely broad outer tails in front of me. Then she flew away to chase an im male RUHU which I manage to nab a tail spread of. This is my most conservative count, realistically there were probably between 6-10 RUHU present, but anyone who has tried counting hummingbirds 1x1 can empathize with knowing how difficult they are to count; so I am leaving this total at the most conservative possible.

Much discussion about this bird. Only later did we independently realize that all six of these photos represent the same individual. After questioning my initial identification as an adult female Calliope Hummingbird, I reached out for expert review. Sheri Williamson wrote: "Definitely not Calliope by gorget pattern and dark lore; R5 with no visible rufous and extensive green on undertail coverts suggestive of Anna's × Rufous." Apparently, though, the large amount of green on the tail and the undertail coverts is at the edge of variation for Rufous. Sheri followed by noting that "normal-length greater secondary coverts" rule out this being a hybrid. Mystery solved - it is a female Rufous.

Locality: Tudor Ave, TM Point,  Private Residence.

Observation Details: Summary: Continuing. Goal was to trap/band/measure fifth rectrix tail feather and rule out Allen's Hummingbird. The hummingbird was not successfully trapped, despite "herculean" efforts by Bob Yunick (bander), "Dillon" (assistant bander from Albany Pine Bush preserve), and the homeowner. Bob was able to view the hummingbird for approximately five hours, and was able to view my documentary photos of the fan/spread tail feathers, and gorget photos. Based on five hours of viewing/ seeing behavior/ and looking at my photos, Bob Yunick believes this hummingbird to be a hatch year female Rufous Hummingbird. Bob was able to view my tail fan/ spread photos and the fifth rectrix tail feather does not seem to have the narrow fifth rectrix. The shape of tail feathers did not indicate Allen's. There were no identifiable characteristics to indicate Allen's. Bob used Peterson's Hummingbird Guide of North America by Sheri L. Williamson and compared the plates to my 8/9/22 photos (see my ebird report-same date to see some of the same photos I showed Bob). The photos did not match perfectly to any of the plates, although it more aligned with Rufous Hummingbird. Although Bob could not view hummingbird in hand (to see two line striation in bill indicating juvenile), his views and hummingbird's behavior indicated likely juvenile. Re: "herculean" efforts to trap hummingbird: Homeowner doesn't have a hummingbird feeder, thus the hummingbird has been feeding on flowers. Bob's trapping system is a hummingbird feeder in a net surround. The net is lifted half way up the feeder, and has a long attached line to where Bob is seated. In cases where a hummingbird is familiar to a feeder, once hummingbird enters the net surround and starts to feed, Bob would be able to release line and net would drop before hummingbird could escape net surround. This hummingbird was not familiar with the feeder and took many steps to feed anywhere and everywhere except the feeder. *For five hours!*.  Bob, his assistant , the homeowner and I came up with many revised steps. The hummingbird feeder was decorated with the hummingbird's favorite flowers, the inside of the net surround contained its favorite flowers.  A large/ heavy planter with its favorite flowers was moved underneath the net surround. The hummingbird fed on all the flowers except the ones near the feeder. The hummingbird started to feed near the planted flowers, and the homeowner covered the favored planted flowers with bed sheets. The hummingbird would feed on the flowers below the sheet, and tried to fly up under the sheet. Then, the hummingbird fed elsewhere in the garden, and the assistant and I sat at the two other planted areas that the hummingbird started feeding, in hopes that seeing us so close to the other planted areas may thwart the hummingbird and send it back to the feeder area. That helped somewhat, but the hummingbird only came close to going inside the net area once (in five hours), but hummingbird was hesitant and hovering closer to the net.  It would have escaped when Bob let net down, and then the hummingbird would be frightened and not return.  The bander left, and then the Ruby-throated Hummingbird landed on a branch in a nearby tree. The Rufous Hummingbird flew in and perched four inches away from the Ruby-throated(!) (that had been dive bombing it). This is not territorial adult behavior. New goal: homeowner is going to set up hummingbird feeder in yard, hoping that this hummingbird will observe local Ruby-throated hummingbirds (there seems to be some territorial disputes between the Ruby-throated and Rufous) and get familiar with the feeder (over a period of days).  And then perhaps then try banding again.  That's *if* hummingbird stays around, and *if* after discussing with bander he feels there may be success in trapping, and he has availability.  This location is private and homeowner hasn't opened location to the birding public. I have included my long notation here, as I have had many messages asking me for this information. I did not take out my camera to use, until after the bander left.  He hasn't seen photos attached to today's report. Photos continue to show tail fan/spread, which also make Rufous Hummingbird seem more likely. Edit: I want to mention that the Ruby-throated Hummingbird was enticed by feeder set-up and was trapped and banded by Bob.

Locality: stakeout Rufous Hummingbird, east of Wheatley (2021)(permission needed)
Observation Details: Adult male. All rufous head, back, and flanks. Dark throat that glowed golden/orange at certain angles even in overcast conditions. Tail feathers were broader than Allen's. Photos taken.

Per Sheri Williamson:  Fortunately, this is a juvenile male by the extensive rufous at the bases of the central pairs of rectrices and well up into the lower back as well as the patch of male-like gorget feathers. Based on tail parameters for this age/sex, the rectrices, especially R5, appear too wide for Allen's, and R2 appears to have a faintly "pinched" tip as is usually the case in juvenile male and adult female Rufous. Even considering the relatively remote possibility of hybrid origin, I'd call this a Rufous.

Coming to feeder. Green back, rufous at base of tail and flanks. While most experienced observers were comfortable calling this a Rufous rather than an Allen's, attempts to capture the bird for measurements and banding were unsuccessful. ID is based upon comments by Sheri Williamson, director of the Southeastern Arizona Bird Observatory, and author of the Peterson Field Guide to Hummingbirds of North America, after she reviewed my photos:  "It helps that this is a juvenile male, which tend to be easier to pin down than juvenile females. The back view is particularly informative in that it shows a) the outer tail feathers (R5) without the foreshortening that makes the front view confusing and b) a broad R2 with a "pinched" tip. Not all juvenile male Rufous have a distinctly "pinched" R2, and occasional Allen's will show a very slight "pinch" farther from the tip on a narrower, more sharply tapered R2, but this bird's R2 and R5 both fit Rufous."

Adult female. Green back. White below with wide orange flanks. Identified as Rufous Hummingbird by Glenn Coady: the tail photo “conclusively identifies this as an adult female Rufous Hummingbird! Your photo #5171 (first photo ML390600251) showing the dorsal spread tail, clearly depicts an obvious lateral edge emargination of R2 (= female Rufous Hummingbird).”  Glenn asked Hummingbird expert Allen Chartier of Michigan to comment: “Luckily, your bird appears to be an adult female, showing the diagnostic "notching" on r2 of Rufous.”  Rufous Hummingbirds have 10 tail feathers or retrices. Starting in the middle and counting out, they are numbered on each side: R1, R2, R3, R4, and R5. R2 is the diagnostic feather to check for a notch/emargination.

Observation Details: Has been coming to the feeders off and on all day. At one point chased by male ALHU/or chased male ALHU off, it's tough to tell. So sweet to see him.  Note: This individual does have some green markings on his back, and I was originally worried about a hybrid or back-crossed bird. However, at one point I was able to capture a photo, albeit a slightly blurry one, of the bird being chased off the feeder by the "resident" male ALHU. In the photo, emargination of the second rectrix (R2) is very clearly evident and outer rectrices were fairly broad, leading me to feel safe calling this bird a RUHU. Additionally, wings and tail appear longer than ALHU which was present and allowed for loose comparative views.

Media notes: Rufous Hummingbird day #4 in Zion, IL (last day present).
Observation Details: See http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S31708075 for original Nov 11th sighting date and info, along with 4 other photos.  I believe this is a Rufous Hummingbird due to photos showing its P2 feathers having a pointed tip (vs. rounded that Allen’s should have).  My guess is that this is an immature male, based on some of the throat feathers showing color (see Nov 13th photos of tail and throat).   Since I was leaving town for a couple months, I knew I couldn't leave this feeder up and strand the bird, so with a number of warm days arriving, I took down the feeder at 2:30 pm.  However, the Rufous kept coming back until at least 3:57 pm (sunset was 4:30 pm today).  It kept flying around looking for the feeder, seemingly confused, at times perching in the White Pine or Tiger Lily dead stalk.  Overall, it evoked sadness inside as one wants to care for such a beautiful and rare bird, but I knew if I didn't take the feeder away, it would surely die once the water froze in it.  This bird stayed from Nov 11th-14th.  It's a certainty in my mind that this bird would have followed the pattern of other Rufous Hummingbirds in Northern Illinois.  That is, show up in early November (or perhaps as late as the late Dec CBC's) and then stay at an available hummingbird feeder until about mid-January when they either expire due to extreme weather or they move somewhere else.

Plumage features point to adult female (throat pattern, wing molt, etc). The bird's R2 feathers don't appear to be emarginated, but the outer tail feathers are quite broad and rule out Allen's. This is the third RUHU that Brian has hosted in his yard!    Tim Shreckengost, Ian Gardner, and I raced up to Camden-Wyoming to see the bird for ourselves. After a few minutes of waiting and watching in the drizzling rain, the hummer shot in out of nowhere and perched at the top of a bush and looked around. During our visit the hummingbird dashed around the yard many times, often perching rather close for extended views, stretching it’s wings and tail as if to show off and allow us the opportunity to attempt to get a definitive ID of the bird. Based on it’s molt, gorget pattern, and coloration we knew it was an adult female Selasphorus; and either a Rufous or Allen’s. Based on how broad the outer tail feathers are, we feel pretty confident calling this a Rufous Hummingbird.    Thanks again to Brian for letting us invade his home and yard for a few hours the other day! This is actually Brian’s third Rufous Hummingbird in the last three years – clearly going to show how much these winter hummingbirds love backyards with a nice garden and a variety of food sources.

Observation Details: Much discussion about this bird. Only later did we independently realize that all six of these photos represent the same individual. After questioning my initial identification as an adult female Calliope Hummingbird, I reached out for expert review. Sheri Williamson wrote: "Definitely not Calliope by gorget pattern and dark lore; R5 with no visible rufous and extensive green on undertail coverts suggestive of Anna's × Rufous." Apparently, though, the large amount of green on the tail and the undertail coverts is at the edge of variation for Rufous. Sheri followed by noting that "normal-length greater secondary coverts" rule out this being a hybrid. Mystery solved - it is a female Rufous.

Secret Garden. Most pugnacious bird in the garden; chased out all the Allen’s from the Pride of Madeira. All rufous. Blazing orange gorget contrasted with dullness of the Allen’s that were feeding here. Also, very loud! I believe the R2 notch is visible in the last photo. This bird favored the large Pride of Madeira plant in the center of the garden.

Confirmed to be an immature female rufous hummer. She has a small orangey/coppery gorget patch and buffy coloration. Confirmed rufous by ohotos of the tail feathers. Theyre too broad to be an allens and lack the notch on the r2 tail feather. Photos following soon.

**County mega - First Brooklyn record.  Very rare regionally otherwise. Thanks to Josh for passing along the report (and hanging a feeder in the park yesterday!!) - found yesterday by Sam V., who reported it as RTHU. Continued today along the path from the feeders down toward Music Island, where it was regularly seen feeding on honeysuckle, which lines that path from top (where the feeder is currently hanging) to the bottom near Music Island/the water.   Initial photos of open tail in the field seemed to pretty strongly suggest RUHU over ALHU.  Seeing some more photos at the end of the day - orange gorget rules out Broad-tailed, and the orange on the flanks and tail get us to RUHU/ALHU.  Open tail photos (which I don't really have, but other reporters [RM and Sean :) ] do) show broad and rounded outer rectrices (R5s), and notched inner rectrices (R2s).  The uppertail was almost all green.  Rufous Hummingbird is by far the more expected of the pair, but aside from that the plumage/feather details don't leave anything to suggest ALHU.

Summary: Continuing. Goal was to trap/band/measure fifth rectrix tail feather and rule out Allen's Hummingbird. The hummingbird was not successfully trapped, despite "herculean" efforts by Bob Yunick (bander), "Dillon" (assistant bander from Albany Pine Bush preserve), and the homeowner. Bob was able to view the hummingbird for approximately five hours, and was able to view my documentary photos of the fan/spread tail feathers, and gorget photos. Based on five hours of viewing/ seeing behavior/ and looking at my photos, Bob Yunick believes this hummingbird to be a hatch year female Rufous Hummingbird. Bob was able to view my tail fan/ spread photos and the fifth rectrix tail feather does not seem to have the narrow fifth rectrix. The shape of tail feathers did not indicate Allen's. There were no identifiable characteristics to indicate Allen's. Bob used Peterson's Hummingbird Guide of North America by Sheri L. Williamson and compared the plates to my 8/9/22 photos (see my ebird report-same date to see some of the same photos I showed Bob). The photos did not match perfectly to any of the plates, although it more aligned with Rufous Hummingbird. Although Bob could not view hummingbird in hand (to see two line striation in bill indicating juvenile), his views and hummingbird's behavior indicated likely juvenile. Re: "herculean" efforts to trap hummingbird: Homeowner doesn't have a hummingbird feeder, thus the hummingbird has been feeding on flowers. Bob's trapping system is a hummingbird feeder in a net surround. The net is lifted half way up the feeder, and has a long attached line to where Bob is seated. In cases where a hummingbird is familiar to a feeder, once hummingbird enters the net surround and starts to feed, Bob would be able to release line and net would drop before hummingbird could escape net surround. This hummingbird was not familiar with the feeder and took many steps to feed anywhere and everywhere except the feeder. *For five hours!*.  Bob, his assistant , the homeowner and I came up with many revised steps. The hummingbird feeder was decorated with the hummingbird's favorite flowers, the inside of the net surround contained its favorite flowers.  A large/ heavy planter with its favorite flowers was moved underneath the net surround. The hummingbird fed on all the flowers except the ones near the feeder. The hummingbird started to feed near the planted flowers, and the homeowner covered the favored planted flowers with bed sheets. The hummingbird would feed on the flowers below the sheet, and tried to fly up under the sheet. Then, the hummingbird fed elsewhere in the garden, and the assistant and I sat at the two other planted areas that the hummingbird started feeding, in hopes that seeing us so close to the other planted areas may thwart the hummingbird and send it back to the feeder area. That helped somewhat, but the hummingbird only came close to going inside the net area once (in five hours), but hummingbird was hesitant and hovering closer to the net.  It would have escaped when Bob let net down, and then the hummingbird would be frightened and not return.  The bander left, and then the Ruby-throated Hummingbird landed on a branch in a nearby tree. The Rufous Hummingbird flew in and perched four inches away from the Ruby-throated(!) (that had been dive bombing it). This is not territorial adult behavior. New goal: homeowner is going to set up hummingbird feeder in yard, hoping that this hummingbird will observe local Ruby-throated hummingbirds (there seems to be some territorial disputes between the Ruby-throated and Rufous) and get familiar with the feeder (over a period of days).  And then perhaps then try banding again.  That's *if* hummingbird stays around, and *if* after discussing with bander he feels there may be success in trapping, and he has availability.  This location is private and homeowner hasn't opened location to the birding public. I have included my long notation here, as I have had many messages asking me for this information. I did not take out my camera to use, until after the bander left.  He hasn't seen photos attached to today's report. Photos continue to show tail fan/spread, which also make Rufous Hummingbird seem more likely. Edit: I want to mention that the Ruby-throated Hummingbird was enticed by feeder set-up and was trapped and banded by Bob.

Private residence.  Access information below.  Stunning unmistakable adult male.  I don't think it has any green body feathers except for a tiny patch on the back of the head.  Back entirely rufous.  Flanks rufous and prominent white collar.  Gorget rarely flashed but appeared orange red.  Access Rules: Visiting Hours: weekdays 9:00 am to 3:00 pm and weekends 9:00am to 1:00pm.   Where to park: Street parking only. Try to limit parking to the front of my house. Do not block any driveways. Option to park at Bellevue Community Center and walk to house.   Address: 1505 Woodsdale Rd, Bellevue Manor, Wilm, DE 19809 Host: Scott Northey Send me a text if you are planning to visit so I can monitor amount of people at any given time (302-354-7321).   No restroom facilities available.   How to view the bird: House is white with green shutters. There are two feeders on the right hand side of the house. Walk across the front lawn to green chairs. Do not use my neighbor’s driveway and do not use my driveway to access my backyard. Please view bird from green chairs or from behind the green chairs. Do not go beyond the green chairs. PLEASE LIMIT the group size watching for the bird to 5 people at a time. This may mean you need to wait in your car until someone ahead of you leaves. Please add these rules to the description of the bird in all eBird reports.

Observation Details: Immature male. Photographed. Bright rufous orange tail with black on the tail feather tips. Green back. Extensive pale orange wash on the flanks. White breast and darker orange undertail coverts. Orange on the head, particularly around the eye and the nape. Heavy green spotting on the crown and throat. Four or five iridescent orange adult gorget feathers were present. While always difficult to judge with certainty, the views I had of the outer rectrices showed feathers that were sufficiently wide to be consistent with Rufous Hummingbird and not narrow enough to be Allen's Hummingbird.

Immature female - Continuing bird that was originally captured and banded by Bob Mulvihill to confirm ID. The bird was heard chipping and calling many times, as it flew around the yard visiting the two feeders and perching in the brush.  Somerset County birder Jeff Payne has been hosting a beautiful immature female Rufous Hummingbird that was captured and banded by Bob Mulvihill to confirm the ID. On November 3rd, my friends and I were able to stop by and watch the hummer off-and-on for almost an hour before heading up to the Allegheny Front Hawk Watch for a PSO field trip. The bird was very vocal and heard chipping and calling many times as it flew around the yard, visiting the two feeders, and perching in specific perches in a handful of short trees and bushes. Whenever I have gone to see wintering hummingbirds, they are always quite aggressive…especially considering how tiny (and out of place) they are. This young female Rufous was no different – during the time we were there we saw her chase and call at Black-capped Chickadees, Tufted Titmice, and particularly one Ruby-crowned Kinglet that just wanted to quietly forage through one bush in the Payne’s yard.

Media notes: Rufous Hummingbird day #3 in Zion, IL (1st Lake County species record).  P2 feather is pointed, not rounded, thus eliminating Allen's as a possible identification.
Observation Details: See http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S31708075 for original Nov 11th sighting date and info, along with 4 other photos.  I believe this is a Rufous Hummingbird due to photos showing its P2 feathers having a pointed tip (vs. rounded that Allen’s should have).  My guess is that this is an immature male, based on some of the throat feathers showing reddish color (however, I'm not sure if that's a confirming mark to separate the sexes along with its age).   Overnight, it was below freezing with medium strength (enough to knock down nearly all remaining tree leaves).  Thus, I kept the sugar water hummingbird feeder inside and brought it out for second straight day at 6:10 am to see if bird would again leave its overnight roost location just to come feed, even though sunrise was still 30 minutes away (at 6:40 am this morning).  Sure enough, the Rufous did just that, so it was extremely eager to generate some internal heat by drinking the sugar water and letting that energize it. The bird was last seen coming to the feeder at 4:34 pm (sunset was 4:31 pm, so second straight day of arriving pre-sunrise and staying post-sunset).  This bird stayed from Nov 11th-14th, when I had to take down the feeder due to leaving for a few months.  It's a certainty in my mind that this bird would have followed the pattern of other Rufous Hummingbirds in Northern Illinois.  That is, show up in early November (or perhaps as late as the late Dec CBC's) and then stay at an available hummingbird feeder until about mid-January when they either expire due to extreme weather or they migrate out when the temps come up alittle bit.

Media notes: Juvenile [Likely] Male Rufous Hummingbird [crooked bill]: attentive and aggressive posture as another Hummer approaches--LOVE this photo! So Feisty!!
Observation Details: One young juvenile ruled the feeder during this time...relentlessly [so I believe it's a male due to the aggressive behaviour]. He has a crooked bill, scissor-like--have heard them hit the screen and windows at times even though feeder is not close to them, so it's a possible injury. However, he is feeding through the bee guards just fine and collects insects from Dahlias and Rugosa Roses nearby--he also followed, then nabbed a mosquito mid-air very close to me. He was extremely aggressive to any other Hummers at the feeder--splaying his tail, chirping like crazy and one time he locked onto another--they spiraled downward, their wings hitting [sounded like a grasshopper] until almost to the ground--then the opponent got free and flew off. He always sat on the same perch--at the back where he faces and chases incoming Hummers. He stayed at his posts [plant supports on either side of balcony] when not at the feeder..from very early dawn to pretty much dark. Amazing to just sit and observe this behaviour for this long this morning! :-)

Continuing, spotted today by Zohara at 9:45, and stayed in view for pretty much the entire next hour or so, but was still there when I left so not sure how long it was seen after that. Going between honeysuckle along path that it’s been on, but also using the feeders regularly.

**County mega - First Brooklyn record.  Very rare regionally otherwise. Thanks to Josh for passing along the report (and hanging a feeder in the park yesterday!!) - found yesterday by Sam V., who reported it as RTHU. Continued today along the path from the feeders down toward Music Island, where it was regularly seen feeding on honeysuckle, which lines that path from top (where the feeder is currently hanging) to the bottom near Music Island/the water.   Initial photos of open tail in the field seemed to pretty strongly suggest RUHU over ALHU.  Seeing some more photos at the end of the day - orange gorget rules out Broad-tailed, and the orange on the flanks and tail get us to RUHU/ALHU.  Open tail photos (which I don't really have, but other reporters [RM and Sean :) ] do) show broad and rounded outer rectrices (R5s), and notched inner rectrices (R2s).  The uppertail was almost all green.  Rufous Hummingbird is by far the more expected of the pair, but aside from that the plumage/feather details don't leave anything to suggest ALHU.

Rufous Hummingbirds are damn cool … because they’re orange. The happiest color. 🧡  Full orange back. Orange throat/gorget with a solid hooded demarcation. Slight flare out at the edges of the gorget. Same body size as the RTHUs. Little white breast patch that faded into orange, like a cowboy style bandana around its neck. Greenish wings. Orange sides and belly. Bright, richer orange tail feathers (top side). Longer bill than RTHU. Feisty and territorial! It perched on the young cottonwood tree and defended the two nearest feeders. Occasionally vocalized when defending.  I had no idea RUHU was a near-endangered species. They are also the northernmost (Alaska) breeding hummingbird species. I'd like to learn more about the tendency of western hummingbird species to migrate east in the fall and winter. It’s wild.

Media notes: Dawn +3.0hrs  ML: This recording combines the raspy "eeech" calls described in BNA account for this species (0:025-0:06, 0:25-0:27, 0:345), with calls comparable to the complex Chatters described in BNA account for Selasphorus sasin (0:22-0:24, 0:41-0:43; see also Figure 3A) and Chip Calls (0:345, 0:365, 0:48-0:50), which I suspect represent contact calls more than warning calls.  The buzzes at 0:13-0:14 and at 0:48 were emitted by the wings as the bird flew off.  There appear to be "cryptic" stop-starts at 0:16 and 0:40.  All times measured from beginning of recording on species reel.  CAM - 2 May 2005]. Habitat: Forest, Wetland, Evergreen Forest, Coniferous Forest, Deciduous Forest, Edge.

Adult female. Green back. White below with wide orange flanks. Identified as Rufous Hummingbird by Glenn Coady: the tail photo “conclusively identifies this as an adult female Rufous Hummingbird! Your photo #5171 (first photo ML390600251) showing the dorsal spread tail, clearly depicts an obvious lateral edge emargination of R2 (= female Rufous Hummingbird).”  Glenn asked Hummingbird expert Allen Chartier of Michigan to comment: “Luckily, your bird appears to be an adult female, showing the diagnostic "notching" on r2 of Rufous.”  Rufous Hummingbirds have 10 tail feathers or retrices. Starting in the middle and counting out, they are numbered on each side: R1, R2, R3, R4, and R5. R2 is the diagnostic feather to check for a notch/emargination.

Following up on a reported hummingbird visiting feeders, it was immediately clear that it was Selasphorus hummingbird. Thankfully the bird was very cooperative and allowed for many observations and photos, including spread tail shots. While not showing a well defined notched R2, there may be a hint of a shallow notch. The spread tail photos also showed rufous extending throughout R2 and a wide R5 which supported Rufous over Allen’s. Rufous is the much more expected vagrant as well. Many thanks to the homeowners for observing and reporting their great find!

Per Sheri Williamson:  Fortunately, this is a juvenile male by the extensive rufous at the bases of the central pairs of rectrices and well up into the lower back as well as the patch of male-like gorget feathers. Based on tail parameters for this age/sex, the rectrices, especially R5, appear too wide for Allen's, and R2 appears to have a faintly "pinched" tip as is usually the case in juvenile male and adult female Rufous. Even considering the relatively remote possibility of hybrid origin, I'd call this a Rufous.

*Rare. Homeowner reports the bird has been present for roughly 2 weeks. An immature male/adult female Selasphorus hummingbird, with rufous flanks, a green back, and a patch of red gorget feathers. At the time of observation, we were unable to obtain spread tail photos, but many photos were taken of the bird.  Upon review of photos taken this morning by Matt Misewicz, the spread tail seems to show wide outer retrices suggesting this bird is a Rufous, rather than an Allen's Hummingbird. I feel comfortable counting it as such - unless the bird ends up getting banded and new information regarding it's ID arises.  Homeowners are alright with people viewing the hummingbird, please park on the street and view from the sidewalk unless invited up. The feeder is in their front yard, on the right side of the house on their porch.

*edit: Sue Finnegan determined to be a Rufous by measurements after eventual banding on 10/23.* Parking very limited, do not go inside fenced garden area as it is not necessary, bird feeds on flowers along the east fence line, give it space and don’t be a dope like some people were at the Virginia’s warbler. Photos. Tail feather shape points to Rufous, at one point Merlin picked up the call notes as Rufous as well for what that’s worth. Had been checking here on a hunch because there were some salvias and other hummingbird plants and this general neighborhood has hosted so many rare hummers over the years. Caught my eye as it flew up into a small locust on the northwest edge, sat preening luckily for me. It got up and did some fly catching around the oaks then headed north into the woods. The rest of the morning it was regular along the east fence visiting salvias, cuphea, four o’clock and zinneas or sitting quietly. Often flew up and looked for insects in, then quietly sat in, a bittersweet-choked tree across from NE corner of garden. Gave chip notes when active. Sue’s attempt to trap not successful as it didn’t want or need feeders. One plot owner has now added a feeder as of this afternoon.

edit: Sue Finnegan determined to be a Rufous by measurements after eventual banding on 10/23.*  Parking very limited, do not go inside fenced garden area as it is not necessary, bird feeds on flowers along the east fence line, give it space and don’t be a dope like some people were at the Virginia’s warbler. Photos. Tail feather shape points to Rufous, at one point Merlin picked up the call notes as Rufous as well for what that’s worth. Had been checking here on a hunch because there were some salvias and other hummingbird plants and this general neighborhood has hosted so many rare hummers over the years. Caught my eye as it flew up into a small locust on the northwest edge, sat preening luckily for me. It got up and did some fly catching around the oaks then headed north into the woods. The rest of the morning it was regular along the east fence visiting salvias, cuphea, four o’clock and zinneas or sitting quietly. Often flew up and looked for insects in, then quietly sat in, a bittersweet-choked tree across from NE corner of garden. Gave chip notes when active. Sue’s attempt to trap not successful as it didn’t want or need feeders. Audio recording at 23:26 minute mark

First alerted to the possibility of a vagrant hummingbird by a post to a local group by Bethany Bergin.  The original finder stated they may have a Ruby-Throated Hummingbird with color abnormalities that has been visiting their feeder for over 2 weeks(!). They also stated noticing differences in behavior. Permission was granted to enter the property and investigate which almost immediately revealed a Selasphorus hummingbird. The bird was buzzing up to the feeder and resting on the metal rings around the tomato plants for about an hour. As my friend and I watched we both noted the bright green back and the rufous sides with a small rufous patch on the rump(base of the tail feathers). We watched for another hour or so and both came to the general conclusion of female Rufous Hummingbird. After sharing the photos and asking around a few others were set on RUHU.. Still not fully convinced after reviewing photos and looking through guides. I returned the next day at around 8 am to find the RUHU at the feeder once again. I studied the bird for another 3 hours or so and noted the shape of the tail and the rounded outer tail feathers (Allens would be more narrow). Photos revealed a small white tip on the end of R2. I also found that when perched the tail did not project far past the wings as you see in photos of female Allen’s. The photos were also posted to an identification facebook group and confirmed by a hummingbird bander that the tail feathers were consistent with AHY/F Rufous.  Many photos, including diagnostic spread tail shots showing tail shape and R2 feather consistent with Adult Female Rufous Hummingbird

Credit to this find to Matt Parsons, who recognized the potential from a really poor Facebook photo, followed up with the homeowner and obtained access. Matt and I went out early to try to document this bird, not expecting to get to species level but there seems to be enough to be confident.  First noted by homeowner November 9. Last seen….  Identified as Rufous / Allen’s complex by broad rufous flanks and undertail, rufous tail bases on R 2-5 (eliminating Broad-tailed).  Aged as adult female by small red central gorget, mostly green crown, mantle and rump and all green R1.   Identified as Rufous by obvious outer emargination of R2 (see pic 1, provided by Mike Bouman and pics 7,8 provided by Dale Buchner), said to be diagnostic by Pyle, Chartier and Williamson. Outer tail feathers as wide as inner, with rounded tips and in no way pinnate.  Additional plumage notes - overall plump bodied with tail that extended about a half centimetre past wingtips when perched. Primaries obviously bowed inward on perched bird. Cheek admixture of green, pale rufous and gray. Slight rufous tone to supraloral, small white post ocular. Throat dotted with greenish, central gorget green obliquely and flashed crimson directly. Flanks bright rufous extending to the undertail coverts. Underwing coverts rufous basally, green lesser secondary coverts. Tail with extensive bright rufous on tail bases of all but inner two rects.

After hatch-year female, banded. First observed by homeowner on 6 November 2021. Notched second rectrix (r2), which is diagnostic for Rufous. Also, measured width of outer rectrix (r5) was outside the range for Allen's. Apparently the first confirmed county record. Last observed on 5 January 2022.

Media notes: perched in shrub
Observation Details: Thanks to the gracious homeowners for creating such a nice birding habitat and welcoming birders to their property to see this beautiful little rare bird. See Ian's post from this morning for a description of the hummingbird, it's activity, and important access information. In addition to flying back and forth between the hummingbird feeder and the shrub across the lawn (~30 ft to the right of the house when you're standing at the white picket fence), it was flying around and perching in other trees, including a hemlock and a red maple. Maybe trying to warm up after a cold night? Best looks were when it was perched in the shrub. Glad our state bird experts where able to differentiate Rufous from Allen's.

Media notes: Track is 5 segments of varying length recorded next to one of the hummingbird feeders; I stopped recording when the bird flew off or when I thought interspecific vocals would interfere (altho the last segment is RUHU, BBHU, and BCHU).  1st short segments is essentially all RUHU until 2 COHAs flew past (yard doves can be heard taking flight at the 16 second mark).  2nd segment is mostly RUHU, but with a BBHU coming in at approx. 39 sec. (running time) and 53 sec. and then multiple birds to the end.  3rd and 4th segments are the RUHU with some other hummers flying past.  5th segment is the RUHU plus BBHU and BCHU.

This bird had been at a residence for a few weeks when I went to see it and managed to get one really good spread tail shot and some other close ups of the bird.  I was leaning towards an adult female rufous hummingbird but didn't have time to really study my photos after the fact due to rushed preparations for a trip.  I asked the homeowner who is a birder to solicit help in order to positively rule out an Allen's Hummingbird.    The home owner wrote this to Sheri Williamson:   "From what I've researched thus far, I believe it's an adult female rufous based  on the slightly pinching on r2, some slight apparent sub-terminal green on r2,  substantial white on the tip of r3, and only mild spotting on the throat. Other  photos show more development of the gorget, which I understand would make it  more likely to be an adult female than a juvie. It's tough with no  comparative Allen's, but R3-5 appear broader than I'd expect to see with an Allen's."  This is the response to my birding friend from Sheri Williamson of the bird based on my tail spread photo:  You nailed it: Everything I see, including the late primary molt and wear on R3-4, is consistent with an adult female Rufous. Great capture of those tail and wing details, too, and a nice record for Midlothian!  So this did confirm the conclusion that I came to in using Sheri Williamson's great webpage on separating Rufous and Allen's Hummingbirds.

(Edit 3 Nov by DPH): Access information as shared on Maine Rare Bird Alert: A Rufous Hummingbird has been coming to a feeder in Port Clyde since 31 October. It is an adult female, so the identification wasn’t immediately known, but photos of the bird in flight were diagnostic. Today, 3 November, Scott Weidensaul visited and was able to band the bird. The homeowner, Alex Brasili, is willing to all visitors to her yard at 787 Port Clyde Road with the following requests: Please limit visitation to between 9AM and 3PM. Park in front of the garage, on the right at the top of the driveway. Be mindful while driving up that there is an older, very friendly dog on the property who “isn’t always aware of cars.” People are welcome to view the feeder, hanging from the south corner window, from the front lawn by the well house, or there are a couple of chairs and a table set out. On that table is also a guestbook that Alex and her partner Justin would appreciate people signing. I’ve set up a stakeout hotspot in eBird for this location and please consider copying this access information into your eBird lists so everyone knows these rules.

Cooperative bird continuing at private property for several days now, observed with permission of homeowner. Made multiple visits to feeder array, occasionally pausing to perch in nearby shrubs between drinking sessions. Photos by other observers show spread tail with wide outer rectrices, consistent with expected vagrant Rufous and contra rarer Allen’s, which has not yet had a confirmed record in New York State. Long overdue state bird for me, thankfully a delightfully confiding individual

UPDATE (11/21/2021):  I reached out to Sheri Williamson (author of "A Field Guide to Hummingbirds of North America") and asked her to review Tim Metcalf's second photo in his eBird checklist (https://ebird.org/checklist/S97347276).  This is her response:  "That's a rock-solid adult female Rufous by both the "pinched" tip on R2 and the width of the incoming R5."  Therefore, I have changed this sighting from "Rufous/Allen's Hummingbird" to "Rufous Hummingbird" and entered it as an adult female.  Original Description (11/7/2021):  Continuing female type, which has been at this location for about 4 weeks according to the home owner.  Small hummingbird with rusty patches along sides and under the wing, green back, fairly straight bill and relatively short wings.  See photos.  The bird's tail feathers appear to be in partial molt so the left R2 (bird's right) is visible in the first photo even though the tail is not spread.  The R2 certainly appears to be "pinched in" at its tip, which would indicate a RUHU, but I don't have a photo of the spread tail so I am conservatively IDing this bird as a RUHU/ALHU until/unless a more definitive ID can be made.  Audio of its chip call uploaded, which is consistent with Rufous/Allen's, but cannot be ID'd beyond that according to what I have been told.

A relatively compact hummingbird (compared the the various Anna’s prevalent at the nectar feeders) with bright orange-buff on the flanks and belly, and rufous on the lower back, above the tail, fading to a speckled iridescent green through most of the back, nape, and crown. However, there were some spots of rufous interspersed with the green throughout the back. The upper breast was clean white, contrasting an irregularly speckled throat. Some buff showed through on the speckled cheeks. Compared to Anna’s, smaller overall, with a proportionately smaller head and bill. It perched on a feeder to drink at around 8:05 am, and was unbothered by the antagonistic attacks of the dominating Anna’s, unlike the Broad-billeds and Costas that are immediately chased off. I did a sketch of it immediately after observation.

Observation Details: Update 7-2-24 Changing to female rufous at the suggestion of a eBird reviewer in response to comments made by David Rankin, a hummingbird expert.  Below is her message to me:  I too thought that this bird had more green on its sides than I have seen before on a female Rufous. An expert from California had this comment though, "I don’t see anything wrong for an adult female Rufous. Some can mostly lack reddish on the flanks, and have greenish in the flanks. Wing shape and length is very Rufous, greater secondary coverts and long and rounded (not short and squared off) and there’s rufous at the base of the tail feathers." (David Rankin) With that in mind, I think we should leave it at Rufous.    Originally entered as a Rufous x Anna's hybrid.  All green back.  Green on sides not characteristic of a RUHU.  There is also rufous on the sides and it seems like there is more then what you would expect to see in a ANHU.  It also looks like there is rufous at the base of the tail feathers but unable to determine how much.  So I'm not really sure.

Continuing adult male

**County mega - First Brooklyn record.  Very rare regionally otherwise. Thanks to Josh for passing along the report (and hanging a feeder in the park yesterday!!) - found yesterday by Sam V., who reported it as RTHU. Continued today along the path from the feeders down toward Music Island, where it was regularly seen feeding on honeysuckle, which lines that path from top (where the feeder is currently hanging) to the bottom near Music Island/the water.   Initial photos of open tail in the field seemed to pretty strongly suggest RUHU over ALHU.  Seeing some more photos at the end of the day - orange gorget rules out Broad-tailed, and the orange on the flanks and tail get us to RUHU/ALHU.  Open tail photos (which I don't really have, but other reporters [RM and Sean :) ] do) show broad and rounded outer rectrices (R5s), and notched inner rectrices (R2s).  The uppertail was almost all green.  Rufous Hummingbird is by far the more expected of the pair, but aside from that the plumage/feather details don't leave anything to suggest ALHU.

Initially thought this might be a Broad-tailed Hummer because of the lack of rufous on the upperside, and the longer tail projection. However we were unsure because of the brighter orange/buff on the flanks, and also the throat pattern with a darker central throat spot rather than evenly spotted seemed better for RUHU. Cecilia Riley confirmed via Kelly Bryan that this is an immature male Rufous Hummer.

Encountered this bird at the feeders on the west side of basin 1. This is where we see the Broad-billed also. He flew in and perched for just a few seconds so I only have these shots of his sides and back. He was pretty compact and small. Straight, shortish bill. His back was green with rufous speckles coming coming through. His shoulder pads were rufous. Tail is rufous and comes to a point where the tips are green. White demarcation separating the gorget from the breast. Only spangled green/gold on the gorget, but he has rufous coming in all over head and neck. I would take a stab at an immature male. Note: this bird looks pretty different than than the one I photographed on 12-14-23. This one has much bolder colors.

Hummingbird not normally seen at this park. However one was seen 12/5 and 12/6. This one is really confusing to me. Small Female/juvenile type with white chest, belly, green above, bright rufous flanks, white under-tail from what I could see.  R1 feathers appear not completely rounded. Light green evenly spangled throat with sharp contrast  from breast. Wings do not reach the end of the tail. Beak is not very long, decurved slightly at the base and has some irregularities. It was not making any vocals I could pick up. The other species I was comparing to was Broad-tailed which is more common than Rufous, but still seldom encounter. I’m posting some photos in hopes a reviewer could confirm. Seen here: (33.2396743, -111.7654640)

edit: Sue Finnegan determined to be a Rufous by measurements after eventual banding on 10/23.*  Parking very limited, do not go inside fenced garden area as it is not necessary, bird feeds on flowers along the east fence line, give it space and don’t be a dope like some people were at the Virginia’s warbler. Photos. Tail feather shape points to Rufous, at one point Merlin picked up the call notes as Rufous as well for what that’s worth. Had been checking here on a hunch because there were some salvias and other hummingbird plants and this general neighborhood has hosted so many rare hummers over the years. Caught my eye as it flew up into a small locust on the northwest edge, sat preening luckily for me. It got up and did some fly catching around the oaks then headed north into the woods. The rest of the morning it was regular along the east fence visiting salvias, cuphea, four o’clock and zinneas or sitting quietly. Often flew up and looked for insects in, then quietly sat in, a bittersweet-choked tree across from NE corner of garden. Gave chip notes when active. Sue’s attempt to trap not successful as it didn’t want or need feeders. Audio recording at 23:26 minute mark

Observation Details: Cont., visiting blooming bush frequented by all the hummers, here: (32.5539369, -117.0861395) 99% orange back, green shoulders, top of head, and a few stray feathers on the back.   Tried my best to get spread tail shots, but mostly failed. The ones I got show a slightly “pinched” left R2 and a more diagnostic “notched” right R2. Not sure how this would have come about… Hybridization? Weird molt stage (immature molting to adult)? The bird is certainly too orange on the back to be a full-on Allen’s, especially with one well-notched tail feather. Reporting as Rufous as my money’s on molt or poor photography over hybridization.

Have tons of photos of this bird. Immature Male/Female. Unreported here, so will leave some comments regarding ID and upload photos momentarily. Shows rufous tones on sides and tail with dark tip. Dark tail coverts, could see white markings as upon further review. Dark smudge in front of eye with white spot behind. White upper breast patch shown well, with slight green and rufous tones from gorget. Underneath the white patch shows a rufuous toned collar going around the belly. All black bill that shows a slight droop to it, but not decurved. Rufuous tones split around a white vent. Dark wings and green irridescent back. Choosing Rufous over Allen's due to range/likelihood.

Media notes: A magenta stripe extends from the base of the bill all the way down to the lower belly at least if not further than where the legs are.  The texture is smooth, looks like all skin, no feathers.  Even the lore has a magenta tone to it, or at least a magenta colored line through the lore.  I will try to get images more front-on to see this better.
Observation Details: Both continuing.  The male has a magenta mark that does not look like feathers, almost like a stain or if it is permanent, some sort of birthmark?  This extends from the bilI base all the way to the lower belly to where the legs are.  The texture is smooth, looks like all skin, no feathers.  Even the lore has a magenta tone to it, or at least a magenta colored line through the lore.  I will try to get images more front-on to see this better.  I know little about hummers and their molts and markings.  This may be unusual or this may be common or simply normal.  I hope someone can tell me as I do not know.  The photos show it.  I hope to get better front-on photos to see it even better.  I do understand that only an adult male Rufous can be ID'd since immature males and females can't be separated from Allen's and sometimes others without being in the hand checking feather/tail detail but for now, calling these an immature male Rufous and a female Rufous, age uncertain.

Credit to this find to Matt Parsons, who recognized the potential from a really poor Facebook photo, followed up with the homeowner and obtained access. Matt and I went out early to try to document this bird, not expecting to get to species level but there seems to be enough to be confident.  First noted by homeowner November 9. Last seen….  Identified as Rufous / Allen’s complex by broad rufous flanks and undertail, rufous tail bases on R 2-5 (eliminating Broad-tailed).  Aged as adult female by small red central gorget, mostly green crown, mantle and rump and all green R1.   Identified as Rufous by obvious outer emargination of R2 (see pic 1, provided by Mike Bouman and pics 7,8 provided by Dale Buchner), said to be diagnostic by Pyle, Chartier and Williamson. Outer tail feathers as wide as inner, with rounded tips and in no way pinnate.  Additional plumage notes - overall plump bodied with tail that extended about a half centimetre past wingtips when perched. Primaries obviously bowed inward on perched bird. Cheek admixture of green, pale rufous and gray. Slight rufous tone to supraloral, small white post ocular. Throat dotted with greenish, central gorget green obliquely and flashed crimson directly. Flanks bright rufous extending to the undertail coverts. Underwing coverts rufous basally, green lesser secondary coverts. Tail with extensive bright rufous on tail bases of all but inner two rects.

Jeff Harvey and I were invited to follow up on a photo of an interesting hummingbird visiting a private residence.  The bird appeared at the hanging feeder within minutes of arrival.  A small, stout hummingbird with a medium length, straight-ish bill.  Pale rufous on flanks and onto chest.  Small central patch of color on otherwise clean looking gorget.  I was not able to photograph the spread tail feathers, but through binocular views the outer tail feathers appeared relatively full and broad.  A possible taper on one of the feathers was also noted.

Locality: stakeout Rufous Hummingbird, Parkman St., Westborough (2016)
Observation Details: Continuing. After a spotty series of visits, the bird has settled into a regular schedule here since Monday, and so now visits at 40 minute intervals on average, although it ranges from 15-90 minute intervals. For example, here are the visit times today: 08:11-08:18, made several short visits, even fly-caught 2 insects from neighbor's maple 09:41 09:58 10:24-10:26 10:50-10:51 11:25 11:54 12:07-12:08 12:48-12:50 13:14-:13:15 13:21 14:10-14:11 15:05 16:03 16:31-16:32 16:55, raining hard, looked like a drowned rat (photos) 17:16-17:17  The bird often flies up into a maple in the neighbor's tree before and after flying down to the feeder. Sometimes it spends significant periods of time at the top of the maple.  Despite several good looks and photos of the tail, nothing definitive can be said regarding specific identification since females and immatures are often impossible to identify without in-hand measurements.  EDIT on 24 Oct 2016- The bird was identified as a Rufous Hummingbird from measurements of the tail while the bird was being banded. More info here- http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S32219624

Continuing for several days. Seen about three times between about 8:45 and 9:00 AM, the  first two times mostly the underside of the tail and vent area, as the bird was perched on the opposite side of a feeder. Also seen by the homeowner during the first few minutes perched in its favorite tree, but I could not see it there. Possibly shot by again at about 9:30.  Not banded by Bruce Peterjohn, but from his review of the photos, he thought this was a Rufous Hummingbird, based on the relatively broad outer tail feathers, and because "the second rectrix (R2) appears to have a slight but noticeable emargination that would indicate it is a Rufous Hummingbird." He also stated that "The bird is clearly a female based on the green central rectrices, but I would not want to speculate on its age based on the tail pattern. Young females tend to have slightly broader outer rectrices than adults, but there is considerable overlap and any differences are measured in tenths of millimeters that would be difficult to judge based solely on photos." See spread tail photo by Max Wilson at (https://macaulaylibrary.org/asset/392350141).  See photos. Many thanks to the homeowners for allowing visits.

Observation Details: Mark's photos had confirmed that the bird was a Selasphorus hummingbird (and more than likely a Rufous), but according to Allen this was a bird that required hand measurements to confirm that it was not an Allen's Hummingbird.   The second retrix, r2 (tail feather) in immature Rufous Hummingbirds are normally notched at the end, except in some cases (here) where it is rounded.  Precise measurements of r1 (central) and r5 (outermost) are then needed to determine the width, which allows differentiation of Rufous from Allen's.  Other measurements were needed to confirm sex and age. Examination of the bird revealed a partially deformed bill.  And, according to Allen "usually females have a dozen or two dozen iridescent gorget feathers (not tiny ones either)". This bird also was showing little-to-no evidence of molt, which is unusual.  Its weight was at the low end of a healthy range, and it showed no body fat.  So, hopefully it'll stay around and find enough nourishment before heading on its way. Allen gave Mark the little hummer to release, and after a few moments in his hands the bird flew to the Sycamore tree overhead, then over to hedges, before making a few passes at the feeder and disappearing over the house.  We didn't stay, and let Mark go out to get more nectar. Congratulations, Mark!  Wayne Co. first Rufous couldn't happen to a better guy!  And thanks to Allen Chartier for the biology lessons! The hummer would return to the feeder just before I left.

Adult female. Green back. White below with wide orange flanks. Identified as Rufous Hummingbird by Glenn Coady: the tail photo “conclusively identifies this as an adult female Rufous Hummingbird! Your photo #5171 (first photo ML390600251) showing the dorsal spread tail, clearly depicts an obvious lateral edge emargination of R2 (= female Rufous Hummingbird).”  Glenn asked Hummingbird expert Allen Chartier of Michigan to comment: “Luckily, your bird appears to be an adult female, showing the diagnostic "notching" on r2 of Rufous.”  Rufous Hummingbirds have 10 tail feathers or retrices. Starting in the middle and counting out, they are numbered on each side: R1, R2, R3, R4, and R5. R2 is the diagnostic feather to check for a notch/emargination.

Coming to feeder. Green back, rufous at base of tail and flanks. While most experienced observers were comfortable calling this a Rufous rather than an Allen's, attempts to capture the bird for measurements and banding were unsuccessful. ID is based upon comments by Sheri Williamson, director of the Southeastern Arizona Bird Observatory, and author of the Peterson Field Guide to Hummingbirds of North America, after she reviewed my photos:  "It helps that this is a juvenile male, which tend to be easier to pin down than juvenile females. The back view is particularly informative in that it shows a) the outer tail feathers (R5) without the foreshortening that makes the front view confusing and b) a broad R2 with a "pinched" tip. Not all juvenile male Rufous have a distinctly "pinched" R2, and occasional Allen's will show a very slight "pinch" farther from the tip on a narrower, more sharply tapered R2, but this bird's R2 and R5 both fit Rufous."

(Edit 3 Nov by DPH): Access information as shared on Maine Rare Bird Alert: A Rufous Hummingbird has been coming to a feeder in Port Clyde since 31 October. It is an adult female, so the identification wasn’t immediately known, but photos of the bird in flight were diagnostic. Today, 3 November, Scott Weidensaul visited and was able to band the bird. The homeowner, Alex Brasili, is willing to all visitors to her yard at 787 Port Clyde Road with the following requests: Please limit visitation to between 9AM and 3PM. Park in front of the garage, on the right at the top of the driveway. Be mindful while driving up that there is an older, very friendly dog on the property who “isn’t always aware of cars.” People are welcome to view the feeder, hanging from the south corner window, from the front lawn by the well house, or there are a couple of chairs and a table set out. On that table is also a guestbook that Alex and her partner Justin would appreciate people signing. I’ve set up a stakeout hotspot in eBird for this location and please consider copying this access information into your eBird lists so everyone knows these rules.

First alerted to the possibility of a vagrant hummingbird by a post to a local group by Bethany Bergin.  The original finder stated they may have a Ruby-Throated Hummingbird with color abnormalities that has been visiting their feeder for over 2 weeks(!). They also stated noticing differences in behavior. Permission was granted to enter the property and investigate which almost immediately revealed a Selasphorus hummingbird. The bird was buzzing up to the feeder and resting on the metal rings around the tomato plants for about an hour. As my friend and I watched we both noted the bright green back and the rufous sides with a small rufous patch on the rump(base of the tail feathers). We watched for another hour or so and both came to the general conclusion of female Rufous Hummingbird. After sharing the photos and asking around a few others were set on RUHU.. Still not fully convinced after reviewing photos and looking through guides. I returned the next day at around 8 am to find the RUHU at the feeder once again. I studied the bird for another 3 hours or so and noted the shape of the tail and the rounded outer tail feathers (Allens would be more narrow). Photos revealed a small white tip on the end of R2. I also found that when perched the tail did not project far past the wings as you see in photos of female Allen’s. The photos were also posted to an identification facebook group and confirmed by a hummingbird bander that the tail feathers were consistent with AHY/F Rufous.  Many photos, including diagnostic spread tail shots showing tail shape and R2 feather consistent with Adult Female Rufous Hummingbird

Immature female - Continuing bird that was originally captured and banded by Bob Mulvihill to confirm ID. The bird was heard chipping and calling many times, as it flew around the yard visiting the two feeders and perching in the brush.  Somerset County birder Jeff Payne has been hosting a beautiful immature female Rufous Hummingbird that was captured and banded by Bob Mulvihill to confirm the ID. On November 3rd, my friends and I were able to stop by and watch the hummer off-and-on for almost an hour before heading up to the Allegheny Front Hawk Watch for a PSO field trip. The bird was very vocal and heard chipping and calling many times as it flew around the yard, visiting the two feeders, and perching in specific perches in a handful of short trees and bushes. Whenever I have gone to see wintering hummingbirds, they are always quite aggressive…especially considering how tiny (and out of place) they are. This young female Rufous was no different – during the time we were there we saw her chase and call at Black-capped Chickadees, Tufted Titmice, and particularly one Ruby-crowned Kinglet that just wanted to quietly forage through one bush in the Payne’s yard.

The separation of immature/female Rufous and Allen's Hummingbirds has to be done with care, and requires detailed photographs and examination of the tail. Even with this, some individuals cannot be safely separated. It is necessary to definitively age and sex the bird before making an appraisal of factors that support one species or the other. Fortunately this individual (at least in my opinion) shows enough characters to support identification.  The center two retrices (R1’s) lack any rufous color in the exposed areas and appear uniformly colored, which is supportive for sexing as a female. These rectrices are also noticeably broad. This, combined with the lack of any visible rufous is good for ageing as a HY.   R2 is noticeably broad and has a thin whitish tip. It only has a faint emargination and a hint of a notch on the inner web (this might also just be wear of the white feather tip as these photos suggest; some have referred to this as "pinching" on the inner web which is more obvious in males, but they are probably not seeing the white area  at the tip of R2). Overall the pattern of R2 is supportive for a HY female Rufous.   R3, R4, R5 show white tips and the tips of these feathers are broad. They do not give a narrow impression, as one would expect with Allen's. Also the rufous in these rectrices meets green and not dark, which is supportive for sexing as a female. The overall broadness of the rectrices tips is good for Rufous.   The uppertail covert pattern is similar to that of the rump and mantle, i.e. green with only thin rufous fringes. Allen’s usually shows obvious rufous color in the uppertail coverts, so this makes a stronger case for identification as Rufous.

*Rare. Reported by homeowner Jenny Forneris yesterday (Nov. 5th) to the Illinois Hummingbird Watchers Facebook Group with a photo, and the post was shared with me by Ryan Jones. Thanks to Ryan, I reached out to Jenny via Facebook last night, and she indicated she'd alert me if the bird was present in the morning and if it was, we could discuss visitation.  As of 7:15 AM, the bird had not appeared, but she then shared at 8:15 AM that it did indeed come to the feeder - and that she was happy to organize some kind of visitation rules (and welcomed me and a few others immediately). I rushed out there from the city and arrived at 9:25 AM. After meeting the homeowner, she and I walked into her backyard where I immediately spotted the hummingbird flitting around in a large tree next to the house.  The homeowner allowed me to make some calls to locals to come check the bird out, and Diane Hicks and Pat Andersen joined me on the scene to enjoy the bird. Andy Sigler arrived as I headed home at 10:55 AM, and Sue Zelek was right behind him.  I discussed visitation with the homeowner, and she agreed to set some times up for people to come enjoy the bird. Today's window was between 1-3 PM, and tomorrow's will be from 8 AM to 12 PM. Pat Andersen has offered to help liaison visitation, and people are encouraged to reach out to her for details and the address, as well as rules on how to access the yard and where to park.  The bird is a Selasphorus hummingbird, with notable rufous flanks and sides, reasonable amounts of rust in the tail, a greenish/gray back and head, and generally pale cream-colored face with a small red gorget spot in the center. While perched, I was able to obtain video of the bird, and eventually it spread its tail, revealing a wide R2 with a notable notch in it, along with wide R4 and R5 feathers. R3 seems to be molting in at present. Combined with the general plumage of the bird and shape and color of R2, Matthew Cvetas posited this bird is likely an immature male.  Many photos and videos were taken, and a massive thank you to homeowner Jenny for allowing a number of birders to come and enjoy this wonderful visitor today!
