Combined with the general plumage of the bird and shape and color of R2, Matthew Cvetas posited this bird is likely an immature male.  Many photos and videos were taken, and a massive thank you to homeowner Jenny for allowing a number of birders to come and enjoy this wonderful visitor today!

*Rare. Reported by homeowner Jenny Forneris yesterday (Nov. 5th) to the Illinois Hummingbird Watchers Facebook Group with a photo, and the post was shared with me by Ryan Jones. Thanks to Ryan, I reached out to Jenny via Facebook last night, and she indicated she'd alert me if the bird was present in the morning and if it was, we could discuss visitation.  As of 7:15 AM, the bird had not appeared, but she then shared at 8:15 AM that it did indeed come to the feeder - and that she was happy to organize some kind of visitation rules (and welcomed me and a few others immediately). I rushed out there from the city and arrived at 9:25 AM. After meeting the homeowner, she and I walked into her backyard where I immediately spotted the hummingbird flitting around in a large tree next to the house.  The homeowner allowed me to make some calls to locals to come check the bird out, and Diane Hicks and Pat Andersen joined me on the scene to enjoy the bird. Andy Sigler arrived as I headed home at 10:55 AM, and Sue Zelek was right behind him.  I discussed visitation with the homeowner, and she agreed to set some times up for people to come enjoy the bird. Today's window was between 1-3 PM, and tomorrow's will be from 8 AM to 12 PM. Pat Andersen has offered to help liaison visitation, and people are encouraged to reach out to her for details and the address, as well as rules on how to access the yard and where to park.  The bird is a Selasphorus hummingbird, with notable rufous flanks and sides, reasonable amounts of rust in the tail, a greenish/gray back and head, and generally pale cream-colored face with a small red gorget spot in the center. R3 seems to be molting in at present. Combined with the general plumage of the bird and shape and color of R2, Matthew Cvetas posited this bird is likely an immature male.  Many photos and videos were taken, and a massive thank you to homeowner Jenny for allowing a number of birders to come and enjoy this wonderful visitor today!

Initially thought this might be a Broad-tailed Hummer because of the lack of rufous on the upperside, and the longer tail projection. However we were unsure because of the brighter orange/buff on the flanks, and also the throat pattern with a darker central throat spot rather than evenly spotted seemed better for RUHU. Cecilia Riley confirmed via Kelly Bryan that this is an immature male Rufous Hummer.

Hummingbird not normally seen at this park. However one was seen 12/5 and 12/6. This one is really confusing to me. Small Female/juvenile type with white chest, belly, green above, bright rufous flanks, white under-tail from what I could see.  R1 feathers appear not completely rounded. Light green evenly spangled throat with sharp contrast  from breast. Wings do not reach the end of the tail. Beak is not very long, decurved slightly at the base and has some irregularities. It was not making any vocals I could pick up. The other species I was comparing to was Broad-tailed which is more common than Rufous, but still seldom encounter. I’m posting some photos in hopes a reviewer could confirm. Seen here: (33.2396743, -111.7654640)

Observation Details: Two Rufous only today, birds "D" and "G" were posing at the feeder for their portraits. Mr Alpha was not much around yesterday and did not show at all today. As this bird began its primaries molt already in early November it may be nearing its time for migration. We shall see.. Bird "D" has molted primaries P1 through P7, waiting on P8-P10. Bird "G": Careful review suggests that primary feathers P1 through P8 have molted and grown in. P10 is in but slightly shorter than the others and P9 is small just getting its growth. Primaries molt nearly over, perhaps a week or two before migration time.

On November 17, 2003 I saw a hummingbird at my mother’s feeder which she hadn’t taken down yet. I called a friend who volunteered at the Carolina Raptor Center and she put me in touch with a hummingbird  researcher. The woman came the next day and caught the hummer in a cage surrounding the feeder. I originally thought it was a female ruby throat. Turned out it was a rufous hummingbird which is rare east of the Mississippi River. She took all its  measurements, then tagged and photographed it. I also took photos of her examining it. Then she let me hold it to release it.

Locality: Spring Mountains NRA--Deer Creek Picnic Area

Observation Details: Summary: Continuing. Goal was to trap/band/measure fifth rectrix tail feather and rule out Allen's Hummingbird. The hummingbird was not successfully trapped, despite "herculean" efforts by Bob Yunick (bander), "Dillon" (assistant bander from Albany Pine Bush preserve), and the homeowner. Bob was able to view the hummingbird for approximately five hours, and was able to view my documentary photos of the fan/spread tail feathers, and gorget photos. Based on five hours of viewing/ seeing behavior/ and looking at my photos, Bob Yunick believes this hummingbird to be a hatch year female Rufous Hummingbird. Bob was able to view my tail fan/ spread photos and the fifth rectrix tail feather does not seem to have the narrow fifth rectrix. The shape of tail feathers did not indicate Allen's. There were no identifiable characteristics to indicate Allen's. Bob used Peterson's Hummingbird Guide of North America by Sheri L. Williamson and compared the plates to my 8/9/22 photos (see my ebird report-same date to see some of the same photos I showed Bob). The photos did not match perfectly to any of the plates, although it more aligned with Rufous Hummingbird. Although Bob could not view hummingbird in hand (to see two line striation in bill indicating juvenile), his views and hummingbird's behavior indicated likely juvenile. Re: "herculean" efforts to trap hummingbird: Homeowner doesn't have a hummingbird feeder, thus the hummingbird has been feeding on flowers. Bob's trapping system is a hummingbird feeder in a net surround. The net is lifted half way up the feeder, and has a long attached line to where Bob is seated. In cases where a hummingbird is familiar to a feeder, once hummingbird enters the net surround and starts to feed, Bob would be able to release line and net would drop before hummingbird could escape net surround. This hummingbird was not familiar with the feeder and took many steps to feed anywhere and everywhere except the feeder. *For five hours!*.  Bob, his assistant , the homeowner and I came up with many revised steps. The hummingbird feeder was decorated with the hummingbird's favorite flowers, the inside of the net surround contained its favorite flowers.  A large/ heavy planter with its favorite flowers was moved underneath the net surround. The hummingbird fed on all the flowers except the ones near the feeder. The hummingbird started to feed near the planted flowers, and the homeowner covered the favored planted flowers with bed sheets. The hummingbird would feed on the flowers below the sheet, and tried to fly up under the sheet. Then, the hummingbird fed elsewhere in the garden, and the assistant and I sat at the two other planted areas that the hummingbird started feeding, in hopes that seeing us so close to the other planted areas may thwart the hummingbird and send it back to the feeder area. That helped somewhat, but the hummingbird only came close to going inside the net area once (in five hours), but hummingbird was hesitant and hovering closer to the net.  It would have escaped when Bob let net down, and then the hummingbird would be frightened and not return.  The bander left, and then the Ruby-throated Hummingbird landed on a branch in a nearby tree. The Rufous Hummingbird flew in and perched four inches away from the Ruby-throated(!) (that had been dive bombing it). This is not territorial adult behavior. New goal: homeowner is going to set up hummingbird feeder in yard, hoping that this hummingbird will observe local Ruby-throated hummingbirds (there seems to be some territorial disputes between the Ruby-throated and Rufous) and get familiar with the feeder (over a period of days).  And then perhaps then try banding again.  That's *if* hummingbird stays around, and *if* after discussing with bander he feels there may be success in trapping, and he has availability.  This location is private and homeowner hasn't opened location to the birding public. I have included my long notation here, as I have had many messages asking me for this information. I did not take out my camera to use, until after the bander left.  He hasn't seen photos attached to today's report. Photos continue to show tail fan/spread, which also make Rufous Hummingbird seem more likely. Edit: I want to mention that the Ruby-throated Hummingbird was enticed by feeder set-up and was trapped and banded by Bob.

Locality: stakeout Rufous Hummingbird, Pheasant Ln., Le Roy (2021)
Observation Details: *Rare and the first McLean County record. Continuing adult male, first spotted by homeowner Brie Martin in late September. Seen immediately upon arrival as it flew into the dead flowers under the feeder in the center of the yard, then fed at the feeder before flying to the evergreen and perching on a string of Christmas lights. Brie then joined me in the yard and we then watched it nectar from the flowers under the feeder and sit in the middle of them for the remainder of my visit. A gorgeous male Rufous Hummingbird, full rufous back and belly, red gorget, white bib below gorget, and pointed tail. In flight, we could even hear the ringing tail feathers. Photos.

Private residence.  Access information below.  Stunning unmistakable adult male.  I don't think it has any green body feathers except for a tiny patch on the back of the head.  Back entirely rufous.  Flanks rufous and prominent white collar.  Gorget rarely flashed but appeared orange red.  Access Rules: Visiting Hours: weekdays 9:00 am to 3:00 pm and weekends 9:00am to 1:00pm.   Where to park: Street parking only. Try to limit parking to the front of my house. Do not block any driveways. Option to park at Bellevue Community Center and walk to house.   Address: 1505 Woodsdale Rd, Bellevue Manor, Wilm, DE 19809 Host: Scott Northey Send me a text if you are planning to visit so I can monitor amount of people at any given time (302-354-7321).   No restroom facilities available.   How to view the bird: House is white with green shutters. There are two feeders on the right hand side of the house. Walk across the front lawn to green chairs. Do not use my neighbor’s driveway and do not use my driveway to access my backyard. Please view bird from green chairs or from behind the green chairs. Do not go beyond the green chairs. PLEASE LIMIT the group size watching for the bird to 5 people at a time. This may mean you need to wait in your car until someone ahead of you leaves. Please add these rules to the description of the bird in all eBird reports.

A molting first year male. I've been entering this bird in my eBird reports as a Rufous/Allens Hummingbird since I first saw him on January 12. I now feel comfortable calling him a Rufous Hummingbird based on the amount of rufous brown replacing the green feathers on his back. I first heard the twittering chip notes of this bird the first week of January. This morning, I again heard his chipping notes and then saw him near my front yard feeder before he flew to his favorite spot, my neighbor's blooming camellia shrub. He spends most of his time there and competes with a Ruby-crowned Kinglet.

Media notes: A magenta stripe extends from the base of the bill all the way down to the lower belly at least if not further than where the legs are. Observation Details: Both continuing.  The male has a magenta mark that does not look like feathers, almost like a stain or if it is permanent, some sort of birthmark?  This extends from the bilI base all the way to the lower belly to where the legs are.  The texture is smooth, looks like all skin, no feathers.  Even the lore has a magenta tone to it, or at least a magenta colored line through the lore.  I will try to get images more front-on to see this better.  I know little about hummers and their molts and markings.  This may be unusual or this may be common or simply normal.  I hope someone can tell me as I do not know.  The photos show it.  I hope to get better front-on photos to see it even better.  I do understand that only an adult male Rufous can be ID'd since immature males and females can't be separated from Allen's and sometimes others without being in the hand checking feather/tail detail but for now, calling these an immature male Rufous and a female Rufous, age uncertain.

*Rare. Homeowner reports the bird has been present for roughly 2 weeks. An immature male/adult female Selasphorus hummingbird, with rufous flanks, a green back, and a patch of red gorget feathers. At the time of observation, we were unable to obtain spread tail photos, but many photos were taken of the bird.  Upon review of photos taken this morning by Matt Misewicz, the spread tail seems to show wide outer retrices suggesting this bird is a Rufous, rather than an Allen's Hummingbird. I feel comfortable counting it as such - unless the bird ends up getting banded and new information regarding it's ID arises.  Homeowners are alright with people viewing the hummingbird, please park on the street and view from the sidewalk unless invited up. The feeder is in their front yard, on the right side of the house on their porch.

By east side of golf parking lot. It would perch on pare branches of trees on NE corner of lot (last tree row before sidewalk) and come down to feed on fire spike or fly to nearby RTHU to quarrel. Comparatively smaller, with large head and small body, short tail. Slight rufous color to undertail coverts, flanks, rump and part of rectrices. Some green-orange gorget feathers showing, mostly on sides of neck. Harsh light but obliging bird! Lifer #1261

All photos were cropped significantly. I left when some maskless non-birders settled down on a blanket upwind from me.

UPDATE 20 NOV 2020 Updated to Rufous Hummingbird from Selasphorus sp.  I ID'd a juv fem Rufous Hummingbird on 16 OCT that appeared in my yard thru 23 OCT.  Today, another hummer appeared (markings on the auricular and flanks show this hummer not the same one that appeared 16 OCT) but being that 4 species can have a similar rufous/buffy appearance, I am going to call this a Selasphorus sp.  (Calliope is not a Selasphorus).    Mitchell and Clark said "Female and immature Allen's are, in most circumstances, impossible to distinguish in the field from female and immature Rufous Hummingbird. Similarity of female and immature Allen's/Rufous hummingbirds to Broad-tailed and Calliope hummingbirds also underappreciated, all having a rufous or buffy wash on the sides and some rufous in the tail. Calliope females have only a limited amount of rufous in the tail, this color usually restricted to the base of the rectrices (usually not visible in the field)."  The third image shows spots on breast and throat including one red and one below it that looks like it is turning red.  I am seeking out others to view the images to get their opinion.  If anyone would like to contact me (besides the eBird reviewer) my email is wildlife.robert@gmail.com.

Jeff Harvey and I were invited to follow up on a photo of an interesting hummingbird visiting a private residence.  The bird appeared at the hanging feeder within minutes of arrival.  A small, stout hummingbird with a medium length, straight-ish bill.  Pale rufous on flanks and onto chest.  Small central patch of color on otherwise clean looking gorget.  I was not able to photograph the spread tail feathers, but through binocular views the outer tail feathers appeared relatively full and broad.  A possible taper on one of the feathers was also noted.
Continuing rarity coming to feeders. Showed up briefly at 8:07AM, then disappeared into the foliage of the nearby Japanese Maple.
Found by homeowner Brian Franks coming to his feeders. Appears to be a HY male.

After careful study of my photos, now that I have access to a computer, I feel more certain this juvenile hummingbird is an immature Rufous.  Shows extensive red tones and has molted to a chunk of rufous colored feathers on the back of the head, where I believe an Allen's would be more green in that area.

Selasphorus hummingbird determined by significant rufous on flanks and tail.  Extensive rufous in tail feathers confirms it is not Broad-tailed Hummingbird or Calliope hummingbird.  Broad and round tail feathers confirming that it is a Rufous Hummingbird not Allens Hummingbird.  The solid emerald green back, and little to no rufous on head suggests a female rather than immature male.

Captured and banded under USFWS and Ohio DNR permits. Hatch-year male. Second rectrix showed diagnostic "notch" of Rufous Hummingbird as well as measured widths of first and 5th rectrix consistent with Rufous. Large amount of rufous on base of first (central) rectrices is indicative of hatch-year male, and this is supported also by measurements of wing and bill.

Continuing bird at feeder; seen by many; not that great photo vouchers attached.  Two other viewers when I arrived; they soon left and two arrived towards the end of my viewing time.  Did not noticeably alter bird's activity.  I observed it visit feeder five times.  First was shortest (less than minute) and was followed by the shortest interval away; most visits were approximately 1 min. long (estimated - I was too busy watching & trying to photo to keep checking my watch while bird was feeding).  Elapsed time between visits was quite variable - shortest a couple of minutes and longest just over 10; I was never as close to feeders as the two there at my arrival (and its 2nd appearance was while they were still there and it stayed there much longer than the first), yet longest time away was while I was lone observer - as was the apparent longest time feeding.  During the time interval between the 4th and 5th feeding visits I observed, the bird spent nearly all of the time perched at a couple of sites in one of the crab apple trees just south of the grain feeders the HOSP were using.  The vast majority of its time feeding was while hovering, not perched.

Immature male. Photographed. Bright rufous orange tail with black on the tail feather tips. Green back. Extensive pale orange wash on the flanks. White breast and darker orange undertail coverts. Orange on the head, particularly around the eye and the nape. Heavy green spotting on the crown and throat. Four or five iridescent orange adult gorget feathers were present. While always difficult to judge with certainty, the views I had of the outer rectrices showed feathers that were sufficiently wide to be consistent with Rufous Hummingbird and not narrow enough to be Allen's Hummingbird.

This bird had been at a residence for a few weeks when I went to see it and managed to get one really good spread tail shot and some other close ups of the bird.  I was leaning towards an adult female rufous hummingbird but didn't have time to really study my photos after the fact due to rushed preparations for a trip.  I asked the homeowner who is a birder to solicit help in order to positively rule out an Allen's Hummingbird.    The home owner wrote this to Sheri Williamson:   "From what I've researched thus far, I believe it's an adult female rufous based  on the slightly pinching on r2, some slight apparent sub-terminal green on r2,  substantial white on the tip of r3, and only mild spotting on the throat. Other  photos show more development of the gorget, which I understand would make it  more likely to be an adult female than a juvie. It's tough with no  comparative Allen's, but R3-5 appear broader than I'd expect to see with an Allen's."  This is the response to my birding friend from Sheri Williamson of the bird based on my tail spread photo:  You nailed it: Everything I see, including the late primary molt and wear on R3-4, is consistent with an adult female Rufous. Great capture of those tail and wing details, too, and a nice record for Midlothian!  So this did confirm the conclusion that I came to in using Sheri Williamson's great webpage on separating Rufous and Allen's Hummingbirds.

Differs from a female Ruby-throated with regards to RTHU lacking flecks on face and throat and rufous coloration under tail, as would be expected with a female RUHU. Adult female - Discovered by Brian earlier in the day. Feeding at various plants around the yard, and hawking insects. Did not visit actual feeder. Plumage features point to adult female (throat pattern, wing molt, etc). The bird's R2 feathers don't appear to be emarginated, but the outer tail feathers are quite broad and rule out Allen's. This is the third RUHU that Brian has hosted in his yard!    Tim Shreckengost, Ian Gardner, and I raced up to Camden-Wyoming to see the bird for ourselves. After a few minutes of waiting and watching in the drizzling rain, the hummer shot in out of nowhere and perched at the top of a bush and looked around. During our visit the hummingbird dashed around the yard many times, often perching rather close for extended views, stretching it’s wings and tail as if to show off and allow us the opportunity to attempt to get a definitive ID of the bird. Based on it’s molt, gorget pattern, and coloration we knew it was an adult female Selasphorus; and either a Rufous or Allen’s. Based on how broad the outer tail feathers are, we feel pretty confident calling this a Rufous Hummingbird.    Thanks again to Brian for letting us invade his home and yard for a few hours the other day! This is actually Brian’s third Rufous Hummingbird in the last three years – clearly going to show how much these winter hummingbirds love backyards with a nice garden and a variety of food sources.

The B&B had at least a dozen sugar water feeders hanging along the deck.  The hummers came and went every few seconds.  We caught quite a few with the cameras. We'll look forward to a review of the photos posted here to try and sort out which was which.  We never did see an adult male in full breeding plumage, only females, juveniles and probably off season males.

The same immature male that showed up and was reported four days ago was  photographed again today. It was determined to be the same bird by the size and location of iridescent red spots on its heavily marked gorget and by the presence of one large green feather extending down onto the right side of the upper tail. But for identification, the tail tells it all: the pinched or nipple-shaped tip of R2 is diagnostic of Rufous Hummingbird, the large extent of rusty colour at the base of all the rectrices strongly suggest that it is a male, and the white tips of R3-5 indicate that it is an immature bird.

Adult male, fully orange back (no green).  Confirmed by fuzzy photo capturing R2 notch in tail feathers while preening.   Observed repeatedly in my back yard in trees and at feeders at distances ranging from 10-40 ft. Very aggressive towards other hummers. Over the last 15-20 years I have had hummingbird feeder‘s hanging in the yard, but have only seen Anna‘s hummingbird’s until August 2017 when I began to see a few persistent Rufous (male confirmed by R2 notch photos) in the yard into winter. (This male appeared to have a partially broken off upper mandible, captured in multiple photos.). They reappeared again this year, 2018, in early February.  Most I have called Rufus/Allen’s, but my sense has been that they are all actually Rufous.

Noblesville.  Female coming to a feeder of a condo owner on the extreme western end of Morse Reservoir.  Actually, the bird was coming to the feeder of two condo owners and both called Wild Birds Unlimited and they in turn called me. I was able to get good looks at the tail feathers. R1 was tipped black distally and was green throughout except for a small amount of rufous on the upper reaches of the feather. R3, 4 and 5 were rounded feathers that were white tipped and contained a large amount of rufous. I obtained fairly decent photos of the bird on November 17, but not of the tail.  he bird was last seen by the host on Dec 2, 2002.

Still at the golf cart crossing and was defending the area from Ruby-throated Hummingbird.  Two subsequent sitings with tail shots will confirm an immature female rufous hummingbird http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S39619314 Bruce Pickholtz http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S39831994 Mark Berney The R1 R2 tail feather's coloration indicates immature female, slight pinch narrowing of R2 indicates Rufous. The R3-R5 feathers are broader at the tips than an Allen's which is even clearer to see in Mark's report and Scots photo in Bruce's report.

Ongoing bird present for many weeks. Rufous Hummingbird with rich rufous sides and belly, rufous in tail and on sides and molting feathers on back turning rufous. Photos were acquired this morning by another birder confirming the identification as a Rufous. Photos attached.  The bird has thus far been identified as an immature female. I think the presence of several large gorget spots on both sides of the neck as well as in the central throat combined with the green feathers molting to rufous in the back are more suggestive of an immature male. Of course the experts will have to make the final conclusion on this subject.

Locality: stakeout Rufous Hummingbird, Parkman St., Westborough (2016)
Observation Details: ***Mega feeder bird. I had just glanced out at the feeders around 8am when I noticed a hummingbird zip away. I thought that due to probability it was likely just a late Ruby-throated. I grabbed my camera and binoculars just to be cautious. The bird returned around 08:30 and then I was able to see the extensive orange at the base of the tail, and the extensive buff on the flanks, undertail coverts, and axillaries. There were a few orange flecks on the center and some dull green spots on the bottom of the throat. The cap, back, and uppertail coverts were a solid iridescent green throughout, and the auriculars were a dull metallic green. The tail did not seem long and broad enough to suspect Broad-tailed. I did not notice this in the field, but the photos show a hint of a buffy supercilium. It returned again around 09:00 when I saw the bird perch briefly. The tail extended beyond the primaries. The bird returned once more around 10am, and then again around mid-day my neighbor saw it. I did not see it for the rest of the day.  Details have been submitted to the Massachusetts Avian Records Committee (MARC).  EDIT on 24 Oct 2016- The bird was identified as a Rufous Hummingbird from measurements of the tail while the bird was being banded. More info here- http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S32219624

Locality: stakeout Rufous Hummingbird, Parkman St., Westborough (2016)
Observation Details: Continuing. After a spotty series of visits, the bird has settled into a regular schedule here since Monday, and so now visits at 40 minute intervals on average, although it ranges from 15-90 minute intervals. For example, here are the visit times today: 08:11-08:18, made several short visits, even fly-caught 2 insects from neighbor's maple 09:41 09:58 10:24-10:26 10:50-10:51 11:25 11:54 12:07-12:08 12:48-12:50 13:14-:13:15 13:21 14:10-14:11 15:05 16:03 16:31-16:32 16:55, raining hard, looked like a drowned rat (photos) 17:16-17:17  The bird often flies up into a maple in the neighbor's tree before and after flying down to the feeder. Sometimes it spends significant periods of time at the top of the maple.  Despite several good looks and photos of the tail, nothing definitive can be said regarding specific identification since females and immatures are often impossible to identify without in-hand measurements.  EDIT on 24 Oct 2016- The bird was identified as a Rufous Hummingbird from measurements of the tail while the bird was being banded. More info here- http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S32219624

Locality: stakeout Rufous Hummingbird, Parkman St., Westborough (2016)
Observation Details: ***Continuing. Today we banded the hummingbird, and confirmed the specific identification as Rufous due to the width of the outer tail feather, r5, which was 4.0 mm. This is too wide for Allen's, but within range of Rufous. All other features fell within normal variation of a hatch-year female Rufous Hummingbird. The bird was captured at 07:57 and released at 08:14. The bird chipped repeatedly upon release from a tree above us. It was seen thereafter returning to the feeder like normal.  Details will be submitted to the Massachusetts Avian Records Committee (MARC).
Continuing bird
Resident female & visiting male. Second resident female not seen today

See photos;  Updating w info from Alex Sundvall:  Sheri L Williamson (http://fieldguidetohummingbirds.com/about/experience/) reviewed 2 photos on the Advanced Bird ID Facebook Page and stated that " R5 does look too wide for Allen's, though that can be hard to judge accurately when there's foreshortening. A "pinched" tip is visible on her right R2, unusual in a juvenile female but indicative of Rufous. The slight blurring makes it hard to see, but there is some rufous at the base of R2. The amount of white on R3-5 plus the tiny spot of white at the tip of R2 are consistent with a juvenile female (second-year females sometimes retain a bit of white on R2, but an older female should show more tail wear)."   https://www.facebook.com/groups/357272384368972/permalink/1106458689450334/

When perched, the bird was very alert, constantly shifting its gaze. It was also very vocal, always announcing it's approach with single or staccato chip notes.

Continuing.  Female Rufous/Allen, evident by rusty orange flanks and central tail feathers.  Have doc photos, but not of an open tail.  Laura Erickson has been able to capture open tail shots showing notched R2 and a thick R5.  I admittedly was unable to get documentation photos of said diagnostic tail feathers from mine and Brandon's observation.  Albeit blurry, here is a screenshot from Laura's video where the notched R2 can be seen, and blunted tipped tail feathers overall, verses the sharp tips of an Allen's: https://imgur.com/E1z5hLu  The above identification criteria was first explained by Alex Sundvall in the Minnesota County Listers Facebook group, which I found to be the most convincing explanation (perhaps the only explanation I had seen) to identify the species from a slash.  Many thanks also to Laura Erickson for such great documentation on her end that I could lean on to feel confident in this life-tick.

First alerted to the possibility of a vagrant hummingbird by a post to a local group by Bethany Bergin.  The original finder stated they may have a Ruby-Throated Hummingbird with color abnormalities that has been visiting their feeder for over 2 weeks(!). They also stated noticing differences in behavior. Permission was granted to enter the property and investigate which almost immediately revealed a Selasphorus hummingbird. The bird was buzzing up to the feeder and resting on the metal rings around the tomato plants for about an hour. As my friend and I watched we both noted the bright green back and the rufous sides with a small rufous patch on the rump(base of the tail feathers). We watched for another hour or so and both came to the general conclusion of female Rufous Hummingbird. After sharing the photos and asking around a few others were set on RUHU.. Still not fully convinced after reviewing photos and looking through guides. I returned the next day at around 8 am to find the RUHU at the feeder once again. I studied the bird for another 3 hours or so and noted the shape of the tail and the rounded outer tail feathers (Allens would be more narrow). Photos revealed a small white tip on the end of R2. I also found that when perched the tail did not project far past the wings as you see in photos of female Allen’s. The photos were also posted to an identification facebook group and confirmed by a hummingbird bander that the tail feathers were consistent with AHY/F Rufous.  Many photos, including diagnostic spread tail shots showing tail shape and R2 feather consistent with Adult Female Rufous Hummingbird

Adult female. Green back. White below with wide orange flanks. Identified as Rufous Hummingbird by Glenn Coady: the tail photo “conclusively identifies this as an adult female Rufous Hummingbird! Your photo #5171 (first photo ML390600251) showing the dorsal spread tail, clearly depicts an obvious lateral edge emargination of R2 (= female Rufous Hummingbird).”  Glenn asked Hummingbird expert Allen Chartier of Michigan to comment: “Luckily, your bird appears to be an adult female, showing the diagnostic "notching" on r2 of Rufous.”  Rufous Hummingbirds have 10 tail feathers or retrices. Starting in the middle and counting out, they are numbered on each side: R1, R2, R3, R4, and R5. R2 is the diagnostic feather to check for a notch/emargination.

Credit to this find to Matt Parsons, who recognized the potential from a really poor Facebook photo, followed up with the homeowner and obtained access. Matt and I went out early to try to document this bird, not expecting to get to species level but there seems to be enough to be confident.  First noted by homeowner November 9. Last seen….  Identified as Rufous / Allen’s complex by broad rufous flanks and undertail, rufous tail bases on R 2-5 (eliminating Broad-tailed).  Aged as adult female by small red central gorget, mostly green crown, mantle and rump and all green R1.   Identified as Rufous by obvious outer emargination of R2 (see pic 1, provided by Mike Bouman and pics 7,8 provided by Dale Buchner), said to be diagnostic by Pyle, Chartier and Williamson. Outer tail feathers as wide as inner, with rounded tips and in no way pinnate.  Additional plumage notes - overall plump bodied with tail that extended about a half centimetre past wingtips when perched. Primaries obviously bowed inward on perched bird. Cheek admixture of green, pale rufous and gray. Slight rufous tone to supraloral, small white post ocular. Throat dotted with greenish, central gorget green obliquely and flashed crimson directly. Flanks bright rufous extending to the undertail coverts. Underwing coverts rufous basally, green lesser secondary coverts. Tail with extensive bright rufous on tail bases of all but inner two rects.

Locality: stakeout Rufous Hummingbird (NO VISIT BEFORE 9am), 34 Clearwater Rd., Brookline (Oct-Nov 2021)
Observation Details: **Rare, but annual (or nearly so) fall vagrant to Massachusetts. Bird has been present at Matt Garvey’s yard for over a week. It was banded by Sue Finnegan on Saturday, October 30 and determined to be a hatch-year female Rufous Hummingbird. After banding it was seen much less frequently (I dipped on my first attempt on Monday November 1st.), but reappeared a couple of days ago, presumably because its alternative food source dried up. It made numerous visits to feeders and flowers during our ~1 hour stay, feeding and vocalizing. Photos reveal the band, assuring that this is the same bird.

***Very rare--continuing bird apparently present since the 17th or 18th, but first reported last night by Derek Lovitch. Found by homeowners. Imm. male Selasphorus hummer with a fair amount of orange on the flanks, rump, tail, and nape, and most remaining green around the back, crown, and shoulders. Showed clean white bib, white throat speckled with rows of dark feathers. Made three stops at the feeder, and visited the flower baskets along the top floor windows along the front of the house, working right to left, and perched several times in a larger apple-ish looking tree with small red fruits. Also perched in a small bare shrub by the white picket fence gate, and twice disappeared into a hemlock in the side yard. Also visited low flowers in front foundation garden. I did not obtain any photos of the spread tail, but Louis Bevier did and confirmed this as a Rufous (as opposed to Allen's) Louis's notes here *Called several times while hovering around a perch, a sharp chip reminding me very much of a DEJU. Also acted aggressively towards PISIs, sometimes chasing them away from the feeders. ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Derek's notes on viewing the bird: "The bird is at 97 Ledgewood Drive in Yarmouth. Ledgewood is a lightly traveled neighborhood road, but it is rather narrow. Please park along one side of the road only (the homeowner’s side/odd numbers) so as not to block traffic. Please be sure not to block any driveways, and avoid turning around in driveways whenever possible. We saw numerous young children out on bikes despite the weather, so please drive very slowly and carefully. Once at the house, walk to the white picket fence on the RIGHT side of the house. The small hummingbird feeder is on the backside of the bay window. The best line for observations and photographs is several feet to the right of the gate. Under no circumstances should anyone enter the yard, neighboring yard, or walk in, through, or on any garden beds. Please include the above instructions in EVERY eBird or any other post...We cannot let people show up with only a GPS location or address and assume they’ll figure out where to see the feeder or where not to be a bother."

Rare and continuing. Seen briefly at one of the two feeders around 10:05 AM and then briefly again from a different vantage point around 10:25 AM before it took off again. Later determined to be a Rufous Hummingbird based on an analysis of photos of this bird by professional bander Bruce Peterjohn, who noticed relatively broad outer tail feathers and that “the second rectrix (R2) appears to have a slight but noticeable margination that would indicate it is a Rufous Hummingbird." Sincere thanks to the homeowners.

First alerted to the possibility of a vagrant hummingbird by a post to a local group by Bethany Bergin.  The original finder stated they may have a Ruby-Throated Hummingbird with color abnormalities that has been visiting their feeder for over 2 weeks(!). They also stated noticing differences in behavior. Permission was granted to enter the property and investigate which almost immediately revealed a Selasphorus hummingbird. The bird was buzzing up to the feeder and resting on the metal rings around the tomato plants for about an hour. As my friend and I watched we both noted the bright green back and the rufous sides with a small rufous patch on the rump(base of the tail feathers). We watched for another hour or so and both came to the general conclusion of female Rufous Hummingbird. After sharing the photos and asking around a few others were set on RUHU.. Still not fully convinced after reviewing photos and looking through guides. I returned the next day at around 8 am to find the RUHU at the feeder once again. I studied the bird for another 3 hours or so and noted the shape of the tail and the rounded outer tail feathers (Allens would be more narrow). Photos revealed a small white tip on the end of R2. I also found that when perched the tail did not project far past the wings as you see in photos of female Allen’s. The photos were also posted to an identification facebook group and confirmed by a hummingbird bander that the tail feathers were consistent with AHY/F Rufous.  Many photos, including diagnostic spread tail shots showing tail shape and R2 feather consistent with Adult Female Rufous Hummingbird

Continuing adult female since 11/19/2021, first arrived at feeder this morning at 6:52 am.  Howard County's 5th definitive record. ID determined by Bruce Peterjohn on Saturday, 11/20/21 after capturing and banding the bird. Per Bruce's examination the bird is...  an After Hatch-Year (AHY, or adult) female Band Number: J45270 Wing Length: 44.75 mm Tail Length: 27 mm Width of Outermost Tail Feather: 4.40 mm Culmen (Bill) Length: 16.93 mm Grooving on Bill: 0 Fat: 0 (on a scale of 0-3) Weight: 3.59 g  Number of gorget feathers: throat feathers were missing due to previous injury  Wing Molt: Primaries #1-2 in sheath, Primary #3 missing, Primaries #4-10 unmolted Body Molt: back feathers were approximately 80% new  We arrived at 9:10 AM on12/4 and the bird was already perched on the trellis near the feeder.  It fed and then and left for about 5 minutes and then retuned after its visit to the nearby trees.  We waited a little longer till it returned for the third and final time during our 45 minute visit.

Locality: Golden Gate Park--Arboretum (San Francisco Botanical Garden)
Observation Details: Immature male Selasphorus with almost entirely orange plumage. No good views of the tail feathers. In the Succulent Garden with several ALHU.  Age / molt notes by Peter Pyle: It's an SY (first-cycle) male and what's interesting is that the gorget has not molted in yet. Usually they do this on the winter grounds but this one will either do it at a stopover location/breeding grounds or may skip it all together and spend its first spring/summer in this (formative) plumage. I have never noticed this before in RUHU. I also just noticed that p8 is growing and p9-p10 are still juvenile. This makes it even cooler! Also the green flecking in the back is an SY character. These may be retained juvenile feathers or replaced green formative feathers or (by the looks of it) both.

**County mega - First Brooklyn record.  Very rare regionally otherwise. Thanks to Josh for passing along the report (and hanging a feeder in the park yesterday!!) - found yesterday by Sam V., who reported it as RTHU. Continued today along the path from the feeders down toward Music Island, where it was regularly seen feeding on honeysuckle, which lines that path from top (where the feeder is currently hanging) to the bottom near Music Island/the water.   Initial photos of open tail in the field seemed to pretty strongly suggest RUHU over ALHU.  Seeing some more photos at the end of the day - orange gorget rules out Broad-tailed, and the orange on the flanks and tail get us to RUHU/ALHU.  Open tail photos (which I don't really have, but other reporters [RM and Sean :) ] do) show broad and rounded outer rectrices (R5s), and notched inner rectrices (R2s).  The uppertail was almost all green.  Rufous Hummingbird is by far the more expected of the pair, but aside from that the plumage/feather details don't leave anything to suggest ALHU.

This was the famous Rufous Hummingbird that wintered in front of the American Museum of Natural History. On NYSBirds-L, I wrote:  "At about 9:30 this morning (1/27), saw the Rufous Hummingbird in her usual area around the entrance of the Rose Center planetarium building, resting and preening on the branches of a bare bush on the east side of the entrance with short bouts of feeding at the yellow-green flowers of the ornamental plants on the west side of the entrance.  She stayed about 10 minutes, then flew off eastward."  I should look at my archives if I photographed her at this time.

Continuing bird. See photo.

Per Sheri Williamson:  Fortunately, this is a juvenile male by the extensive rufous at the bases of the central pairs of rectrices and well up into the lower back as well as the patch of male-like gorget feathers. Based on tail parameters for this age/sex, the rectrices, especially R5, appear too wide for Allen's, and R2 appears to have a faintly "pinched" tip as is usually the case in juvenile male and adult female Rufous. Even considering the relatively remote possibility of hybrid origin, I'd call this a Rufous.

Continuing rarity. Bird had molt in wing (visible in photos) likely indivating after hatch year bird. Also colored gorget feathers appeared green in some photos. White spots on tail feathers and tail feather shape broad (like Rufous vs narrow like Allen's). All this points towards adult female Rufous Hummingbird, but I have heard Bruce Peterjohn is obtaining permission to band this bird, so we'll see.  The bird was absent when I arrived, but maybe after half an hour flew into the feeder, fed and then spent much time perched atop a vine on the arbor close to the feeder, making a few more back and forth visits. Not shy, despite the birder/photographer paparazzi gathered to photograph it (well spaced and masked).

Adult female, rufous sides of white breast, smaller solid triangular gorget patch. Previously banded last winter in Mobile AL. Information from bander per Clarke email to BRAC email list: Band #K57632 on December 23, 2018 near Mobile AL December 3, 2020 Mark Armstrong collected data: wing measurement of 44.27mm, tail 27mm, beak 17.80mm, ~18 gorget feathers, weight 3.3 grams and no visible fat. The second tail feather had a definite tipped shape which would never be seen on an Allen’s.  The 5th tail feather was relatively broad and an Allen’s would be much thinner.

UPDATE 20 NOV 2020 Updated to Rufous Hummingbird from Selasphorus sp.  I ID'd a juv fem Rufous Hummingbird on 16 OCT that appeared in my yard thru 23 OCT.  Today, another hummer appeared (markings on the auricular and flanks show this hummer not the same one that appeared 16 OCT) but being that 4 species can have a similar rufous/buffy appearance, I am going to call this a Selasphorus sp.  (Calliope is not a Selasphorus).    Mitchell and Clark said "Female and immature Allen's are, in most circumstances, impossible to distinguish in the field from female and immature Rufous Hummingbird. Similarity of female and immature Allen's/Rufous hummingbirds to Broad-tailed and Calliope hummingbirds also underappreciated, all having a rufous or buffy wash on the sides and some rufous in the tail. Calliope females have only a limited amount of rufous in the tail, this color usually restricted to the base of the rectrices (usually not visible in the field)."  The third image shows spots on breast and throat including one red and one below it that looks like it is turning red.  I am seeking out others to view the images to get their opinion.  If anyone would like to contact me (besides the eBird reviewer) my email is wildlife.robert@gmail.com.
